{"title_page": "Adam White (zoologist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n | name              = Adam White\n | image             = Portrait of Adam White.jpg\n | image_size        =\n | alt               =\n | caption           = Portrait by Norman Macbeth, 1846.\n | birth_name        = \n | birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1817|04|29}}\n | birth_place       = [[Edinburgh]]\n | death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1878|12|30|1817|04|29}}  \n | resting_place     = [[Pollokshields]]\n | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n | residence         =\n | citizenship       =\n | nationality       = Scottish\n | fields            = Entomology, carcinology\n | workplaces        = [[British Museum]]\n | alma_mater        =\n | known_for         = \n | author_abbrev_bot =\n | author_abbrev_zoo =\n | influences        =\n | influenced        =\n | awards            = \n | spouse            =\n | relatives         =\n | signature         =\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n'''Adam White''' (29 April 1817 \u2013 30 December 1878) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[zoologist]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nWhite was born in [[Edinburgh]] on 29 April 1817.<ref name=\"DNB\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/29234 White, Adam (1817-1878), naturalist] by Ann Datta in the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''. {{DNBfirst|wstitle=White, Adam}}</ref> He became acquainted with [[John Edward Gray]], [[Keeper of Zoology]] at the [[British Museum]]. At the age of eighteen, White obtained a post in the Museum in the Zoology Department.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>  In 1841 he was given the task of identifying and publishing the spiders collected by [[Charles Darwin]] on the [[Second voyage of HMS Beagle|Voyage of the Beagle]] and \"preserved in spirits of wine, as spiders should always be if possible\".  This work was published as ''Description of new or little known Arachnida''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kohn (ed)|first1=David|title=The Darwinian Heritage|date=14 July 2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|page=1014|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fr7_AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1012&lpg=PA1012|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhite specialised in [[insect]]s and [[crustacean]]s, writing the ''List of the Specimens of Crustacea in the British Museum'' (1847) and ''A Popular History of Mammalia'' (1850).<ref name=\"DNB\"/> White was a member of the [[Entomological Society of London]] from 1839 to 1863, and a Fellow of the [[Linnean Society]] from 1846 to 1855.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nWhite suffered a [[nervous breakdown]] after the death of his first wife in 1861. He remarried in 1862, and had at least three children by his second wife. He died [[intestacy|intestate]] in [[Pollokshields]] on 30 December 1878.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Species named in White's honour==\n[[John O. Westwood|John Obadiah Westwood]] named the insect species ''[[Taphroderes whitii]]'' in White's honour, after White pointed a specimen of that same insect out to Westwood during a visit to the British Museum.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Westwood|first1=John Obediah|title=The cabinet of oriental entomology |date=1848 |publisher=William Smith|location=London, United Kingdom |page=32 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/24607961#page/106/mode/1up|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |author=Adam White |year=1841 |chapter=Appendix F. Notes on some insects from King George's Sound |chapter-url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.hwxl54;view=1up;seq=490 |editor=G. Grey |title=Journals of Two Expeditions of Discovery in North-West and Western Australia |volume=2 |publisher=T. & W. Boone |location=London |pages=450\u2013456}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1844 |title=Descriptions of some new species of Coleoptera and Homoptera from China |journal=[[Annals and Magazine of Natural History]] |volume=1 |issue=14 |pages=422\u2013426 |url=http://biostor.org/reference/60325}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1844 |title=Description of some coleopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum apparently unnoticed |journal=[[Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London]] |volume=24 |pages=8\u201317, 406\u2013410}}\n*{{cite book |author=Adam White |year=1846 |chapter=Insects of New Zealand |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/zoologyofvoyageo02rich#page/n187/mode/2up |editor=J. Richardson & J. E. Gray |title=The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. ''Erebus'' & ''Terror'' under Command of Captain Sir J. C. Ross, during the years 1839\u20131843 |publisher=E. W. Janson |location=London |volume=2 |pages=1\u201351}}\n*{{cite book |author=Adam White |year=1847 |title=Nomenclature of Coleopterous Insects in the Collection of the British Museum |chapter=Cetoniadae |chapter-url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/37976#page/7/mode/1up |publisher=Spottiswoode & Shaw |location=London |pages=1\u201356}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1859 |title=Spicilegia Entomologica. IV. Diagnoses Coleopterorum quatuor |journal=[[Annals and Magazine of Natural History]] |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=290\u2013291 |url=http://biostor.org/reference/65402}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1859 |title=Descriptions of unrecorded species of Australian Coleoptera of the families Carabidae, Buprestidae, Lamellicornia, Longicornia etc |journal=[[Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London]] |pages=117\u2013123 |url=http://biostor.org/reference/60452}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | author = Clark Paul F., Presswell Bronwen | year = 2001 | title = Adam White: The Crustacean Years | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140809213208/http://lkcnhm.nus.edu.sg/rbz/biblio/49/49rbz149-166.pdf | format = PDF | journal = The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology | volume = 49 | issue = 1| pages = 149\u2013166 }}\n* {{cite journal | author = Stevenson O.J. | year = 1907 | title = The Eccentricities of Genius | url = https://archive.org/stream/canadianmagazine29torouoft#page/n7/mode/2up | journal = The Canadian Magazine | volume = 29 | issue = 1| pages = 3\u20139 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{gutenberg author | id=Adam_White | name=Adam White}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Adam White |birth=1817 |death=1878 |sopt=t }}\n* {{Librivox author |id=9622}}\n* [http://darwin-online.org.uk/EditorialIntroductions/Freeman_TestimonialsofAdamWhite.html Testimonials of Adam White]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Adam}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish zoologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish entomologists]]\n[[Category:British carcinologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish lepidopterists]]\n[[Category:Employees of the Natural History Museum, London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n | name              = Adam White\n | image             = Portrait of Adam White.jpg\n | image_size        =\n | alt               =\n | caption           = Portrait by Norman Macbeth, 1846.\n | birth_name        = \n | birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1817|04|29}}\n | birth_place       = [[Edinburgh]]\n | death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1878|12|30|1817|04|29}}  \n | resting_place     = [[Pollokshields]]\n | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n | residence         =\n | citizenship       =\n | nationality       = Scottish\n | fields            = Entomology, carcinology\n | workplaces        = [[British Museum]]\n | alma_mater        =\n | known_for         = \n | author_abbrev_bot =\n | author_abbrev_zoo =\n | influences        =\n | influenced        =\n | awards            = \n | spouse            =\n | relatives         =\n | signature         =\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n'''Adam White''' (29 April 1817 \u2013 30 December 1878) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[zoologist]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nWhite was born in [[Edinburgh]] on 29 April 1817.<ref name=\"DNB\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/29234 White, Adam (1817-1878), naturalist] by Ann Datta in the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''. {{DNBfirst|wstitle=White, Adam}}</ref> He became acquainted with [[John Edward Gray]], [[Keeper of Zoology]] at the [[British Museum]]. At the age of eighteen, White obtained a post in the Museum in the Zoology Department.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>  In 1841 he was given the task of identifying and publishing the spiders collected by [[Charles Darwin]] on the [[Second voyage of HMS Beagle|Voyage of the Beagle]] and \"preserved in spirits of wine, as spiders should always be if possible\".  This work was published as ''Description of new or little known Arachnida''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kohn (ed)|first1=David|title=The Darwinian Heritage|date=14 July 2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|page=1014|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fr7_AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1012&lpg=PA1012|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhite specialised in [[insect]]s and [[crustacean]]s, writing the ''List of the Specimens of Crustacea in the British Museum'' (1847) and ''A Popular History of Mammalia'' (1850).<ref name=\"DNB\"/> White was a member of the [[Entomological Society of London]] from 1839 to 1863, and a Fellow of the [[Linnean Society]] from 1846 to 1855.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nWhite suffered a [[nervous breakdown]] after the death of his first wife in 1861. He remarried in 1862, and had at least three children by his second wife. He died [[intestacy|intestate]] in [[Pollokshields]] on 30 December 1878.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Species named in White's honour==\n[[John O. Westwood|John Obadiah Westwood]] named the insect species ''[[Taphroderes whitii]]'' in White's honour, after White pointed a specimen of that same insect out to Westwood during a visit to the British Museum.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Westwood|first1=John Obediah|title=The cabinet of oriental entomology |date=1848 |publisher=William Smith|location=London, United Kingdom |page=32 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/24607961#page/106/mode/1up|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |author=Adam White |year=1841 |chapter=Appendix F. Notes on some insects from King George's Sound |chapter-url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.hwxl54;view=1up;seq=490 |editor=G. Grey |title=Journals of Two Expeditions of Discovery in North-West and Western Australia |volume=2 |publisher=T. & W. Boone |location=London |pages=450\u2013456}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1844 |title=Descriptions of some new species of Coleoptera and Homoptera from China |journal=[[Annals and Magazine of Natural History]] |volume=1 |issue=14 |pages=422\u2013426 |url=http://biostor.org/reference/60325}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1844 |title=Description of some coleopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum apparently unnoticed |journal=[[Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London]] |volume=24 |pages=8\u201317, 406\u2013410}}\n*{{cite book |author=Adam White |year=1846 |chapter=Insects of New Zealand |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/zoologyofvoyageo02rich#page/n187/mode/2up |editor=J. Richardson & J. E. Gray |title=The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. ''Erebus'' & ''Terror'' under Command of Captain Sir J. C. Ross, during the years 1839\u20131843 |publisher=E. W. Janson |location=London |volume=2 |pages=1\u201351}}\n*{{cite book |author=Adam White |year=1847 |title=Nomenclature of Coleopterous Insects in the Collection of the British Museum |chapter=Cetoniadae |chapter-url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/37976#page/7/mode/1up |publisher=Spottiswoode & Shaw |location=London |pages=1\u201356}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1859 |title=Spicilegia Entomologica. IV. Diagnoses Coleopterorum quatuor |journal=[[Annals and Magazine of Natural History]] |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=290\u2013291 |url=http://biostor.org/reference/65402}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Adam White |year=1859 |title=Descriptions of unrecorded species of Australian Coleoptera of the families Carabidae, Buprestidae, Lamellicornia, Longicornia etc |journal=[[Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London]] |pages=117\u2013123 |url=http://biostor.org/reference/60452}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Clark, Paul F., & Bronwen Presswell (2001). [https://web.archive.org/web/20140809213208/http://lkcnhm.nus.edu.sg/rbz/biblio/49/49rbz149-166.pdf \"Adam White: The Crustacean Years,\"] ''The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology'' '''49''' (1), pp.&nbsp;149\u2013166.\n* Stevenson, O.J. (1907). [https://archive.org/stream/canadianmagazine29torouoft#page/n7/mode/2up \"The Eccentricities of Genius,\"] ''The Canadian Magazine'' '''29''' (1), pp.&nbsp;3\u20139.\n\n==External links==\n* {{gutenberg author | id=Adam_White | name=Adam White}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Adam White |birth=1817 |death=1878 |sopt=t }}\n* {{Librivox author |id=9622}}\n* [http://darwin-online.org.uk/EditorialIntroductions/Freeman_TestimonialsofAdamWhite.html Testimonials of Adam White]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Adam}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish zoologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish entomologists]]\n[[Category:British carcinologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish lepidopterists]]\n[[Category:Employees of the Natural History Museum, London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Journal cites:, templated 2 journal cites (Diberri fmt authors)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_White_(zoologist)"}
{"title_page": "Hyperbolastic functions", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Figure 1 - Hyperbolastic Type I.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type I function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 2 - Hyperbolastic Type I.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type I function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 3 - Hyperbolastic Type II.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type II function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 4 - Hyperbolastic Type II.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type II function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 5 - Hyperbolastic Type III.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type III function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 6 - Hyperbolastic Type III.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic cumulative distribution function of type III with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 7 - Hyperbolastic Type III.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic probability density function of type III with varying parameter values.]]\n\nThe '''hyperbolastic functions''' are [[Function (mathematics)|mathematical functions]] that are used in medical [[statistical modeling]]. These models were originally developed to capture the growth dynamics of multicellular tumor spheres, and were introduced in 2005 by Mohammad Tabatabai, David Williams, and Zoran Bursac<ref name=\"Tabatabai 2005\">{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1742-4682-2-14 |year = 2005 |last1 = Tabatabai |first1 = Mohammad |last2 = Williams |first2 = David |last3 = Bursac |first3 = Zoran |title = Hyperbolastic growth models: Theory and application |journal = Theoretical Biology and Medical Modelling |volume = 2 |pages = 14 |pmid = 15799781 |pmc = 1084364}}</ref> The precision of hyperbolastic functions in modeling real world problems is somewhat due to their flexibility in their point of inflection.<ref name=\"Tabatabai 2005\" /> These functions can be used in a wide variety of modeling problems such as tumor growth, stem cell proliferation, pharma kinetics, cancer growth, sigmoid activation function in neural networks, and epidemiological disease progression or regression.<ref name=\"Tabatabai 2005\" />\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic functions'' can model both growth and decay curves until it reaches carrying capacity. Due to their flexibility, \nthese models have diverse applications in the medical field, with the ability to capture disease progression with an intervening\ntreatment. As the figures indicate, the ''hyperbolastic functions'' can fit a sigmoidal curve indicating that the slowest rate occurs at \nthe early and late stages. In addition to the presenting sigmoidal shapes, it can also accommodate biphasic situations where medical  \ninterventions slow or reverse disease progression; but, when the effect of the treatment vanishes, the disease will begin the \nsecond phase of its progression until it reaches it's horizontal asymptote.\n\nOne of the main characteristics these functions have is that they cannot only fit sigmoidal shapes, but can also model biphasic growth patterns that other classical sigmoidal curves cannot adequately model. This distinguishing feature has advantageous applications in various fields including medicine, biology, economics, and engineering.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1099/mic.0.25880-0|title = Biphasic kinetics of growth and bacteriocin production with Lactobacillus amylovorus DCE 471 occur under stress conditions|year = 2003|last1 = Neysens|first1 = Patricia|last2 = Messens|first2 = Winy|last3 = Gevers|first3 = Dirk|last4 = Swings|first4 = Jean|last5 = De Vuyst|first5 = Luc|journal = Microbiology|volume = 149|issue = 4|pages = 1073\u20131082|pmid = 12686649}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Chu |first=Charlene |last2=Han |first2=Christina  |last3=Shimizu |first3=Hiromi  |last4=Wong |first4=Bonnie  |title=The Effect of Fructose, Galactose, and Glucose on the Induction of \u03b2-Galactosidase in ''Escherichia coli'' |url=https://www.microbiology.ubc.ca/sites/default/files/roles/drupal_ungrad/JEMI/2/2-1.pdf |year=2002 |journal=Journal of Experimental Microbiology and Immunology |volume=2 |pages=1\u20135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3934/mbe.2013.10.925| title=T model of growth and its application in systems of tumor-immunedynamics| journal=Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering| year=2013| volume=10| issue=3| pages=925\u2013938| pmid=23906156| last1=Tabatabai| first1=M. A.| last2=Eby| first2=W. M.| last3=Singh| first3=K. P.| last4=Bae| first4=S.| pmc=4476034}}</ref>\n\n=== Function H1 ===\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic rate equation of type I'', denoted H1, is given by:\n\n<math display =\"block\">\\frac{dP(x)}{dx}= \\frac{P(x)}{M} \\left(M-P \\left(x\\right)\\right)\\left(\\delta+\\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}\\right),</math>\n\nwhere <math>x</math> is any real number and \n<math>P\\left(x \\right)</math> is the population size at <math>x</math>. The parameter <math>M</math> represents carrying capacity, and parameters <math>\\delta</math> and <math>\\theta</math> jointly represent growth rate. The parameter <math>\\theta</math> gives the distance from a symmetric sigmoidal curve. Solving the hyperbolastic rate equation of type I for <math>P \\left(x \\right)</math> gives:\n\n<math display =\"block\">P(x)= \\frac{M}{1+ \\alpha e^{-\\delta x- \\theta \\operatorname{arsinh}(x)}},</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\operatorname{arsinh}</math> is the inverse hyperbolic sine function. If one desires to use the initial condition <math>P\\left(x_0\\right)=P_0</math>, then <math>\\alpha</math> can be expressed as:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\frac{M-P_0}{P_0} e^{\\delta x_0+ \\theta \\operatorname{arsinh}(x_0)}</math>.\n\nIf <math>x_0=0</math>, then <math>\\alpha</math> reduces to:\n\n:<math>\\alpha= \\frac{M-P_0}{P_0}</math>.\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic function of type I'' generalizes the [[logistic function]]. If the parameters <math>\\theta = 0</math>, then it would become a logistic function. This function <math>P(x)</math> is a ''hyperbolastic function of type I''. The ''standard hyperbolastic function of type I'' is\n\n:<math>P(x)= \\frac{1}{1+ e^{-x- \\operatorname{arsinh}(x)}}</math>.\n\n=== Function H2 ===\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic rate equation of type II'', denoted by H2, is defined as:\n\n:<math>\\frac{dP(x)}{dx}= \\frac{\\alpha \\delta \\gamma P^2 (x) x^{\\gamma - 1}}{M} \\tanh \\left(\\frac{M-P(x)}{\\alpha P(x)}\\right),</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\tanh</math> is the hyperbolic tangent function, <math>M</math> is the carrying capacity, and both <math>\\delta</math> and <math>\\gamma>0</math> jointly determine the growth rate. In addition, the parameter <math>\\gamma</math> represents acceleration in the time course. Solving the hyperbolastic rate function of type II for <math>P\\left(x\\right)</math> gives:\n\n:<math>P(x)=\\frac{M}{1+\\alpha\\operatorname{arsinh} \\left(e^{-\\delta x^\\gamma}\\right)}\n</math>.\n\nIf one desires to use initial condition <math>\nP(x_0)=P_0,</math> then <math>\\alpha</math> can be expressed as:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\frac{M-P_0}{P_0 \\operatorname{arsinh} \\left(e^{-\\delta x_0^\\gamma}\\right)}\n</math>.\n\nIf <math>x_0=0</math>, then <math>\\alpha</math> reduces to:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\frac{M-P_0}{P_0 \\operatorname{arsinh} (1)}</math>.\n\nThe ''standard hyperbolastic function of type II'' is defined as:\n\n:<math>P(x)=\\frac{1}{1+ \\operatorname{arsinh} \\left(e^{-x}\\right)}\n</math>.\n\n=== Function H3 ===\n\nThe hyperbolastic rate equation of type III is denoted by H3 and has the form:\n\n:<math>\\frac{dP(t)}{dt}= \\left(M-P \\left(t \\right)\\right)\\left(\\delta \\gamma t^{\\gamma - 1}+ \\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+ \\theta^2 t^2}}\\right)</math>,\n\nwhere <math>t</math> > 0. The parameter <math>M</math> represents the carrying capacity, and the parameters <math>\\delta,</math> <math>\\gamma,</math> and <math>\\theta</math> jointly determine the growth rate. The parameter <math>\\gamma,</math> represents acceleration of the time scale, while the size of <math>\\theta</math> represents distance from a symmetric sigmoidal curve. The solution to the differential equation of type III is:\n\n:<math>P(t)= M- \\alpha e^{-\\delta t^\\gamma- \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta t)}</math>,\n\nwith the initial condition <math>\nP\\left(t_0\\right)=P_0</math> we can express <math>\\alpha</math> as:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\left(M-P_0 \\right) e^{\\delta t_0^\\gamma+ \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta t_0)}</math>.\n\nThe standard hyperbolastic of type III is defined as:\n\n:<math>P\\left(t\\right)=1-e^{-t- \\operatorname{arsinh}(t)}</math>.\n\nThe hyperbolastic distribution of type III is a three-parameter family of continuous probability distributions with scale parameters <math>\\delta</math> > 0, and <math>\\theta</math> \u2265 0 and parameter <math>\\gamma</math> as the shape parameter. When the parameter <math>\\theta</math> = 0, the hyperbolastic distribution of type III is reduced to the Weibull distribution. The hyperbolastic cumulative distribution function is given by:\n\n:<math>F(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta)=\n\\begin{cases}\n1- e^{-\\delta x^\\gamma - \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta x)} & x\\geq0 ,\\\\\n0 & x < 0\n\\end{cases}\n</math>,\n\nand its corresponding probability density function is:\n\n:<math>\nf(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta) =\n\\begin{cases}\ne^{- \\delta x^\\gamma - \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta x)}\\left(\\delta \\gamma x^{\\gamma-1}+ \\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+\\theta^2 x^2}}\\right) & x\\geq0 ,\\\\\n0 & x<0\n\\end{cases}</math>.\n\nThe hazard function <math>h</math> (or failure rate) is given by:\n\n:<math>h\\left(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta \\right) = \\delta\\gamma x^{\\gamma-1} + \\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+ x^2\\theta^2}}.</math>\n\nThe survival function <math>S</math> is given by:\n\n:<math>S(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta)= e^{- \\delta x^\\gamma- \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta x)}.</math>\n\n===Properties===\n\nIf one desires to calculate the point <math>x</math> where the population reaches a percentage of its carrying capacity <math>M</math>, then \none can solve the equation:\n:<math>P(x) = k M</math> \nfor <math>x</math>, where <math>0 < k < 1</math>. For instance, the half point can be found by setting <math>k= \\frac{1}{2}</math>.\n\n===Applications===\n\nAccording to stem cell researchers at McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine at the University of Pittsburgh, \"a newer model [called the hyperbolastic type III or] H3 is a differential equation that also describes the cell growth. This model allows for much more variation and has been proven to better predict growth.\"<ref>{{cite document |vauthors=Roehrs T, Bogdan P, Gharaibeh B, et al. |date=n.d. |title=Proliferative heterogeneity in stem cell populations |url=https://www.engineering.pitt.edu/Departments/Bioengineering/_Documents/Undergraduate-research/Intramural-Internships/(2131)---Fall2012/Abstract_Roehrs |publisher=Live Cell Imaging Laboratory, McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine}}</ref>\n\nThe hyperbolastic growth models H1, H2, and H3 have been applied to analyze the growth of solid [[Ehrlich carcinoma]] using a variety of treatments.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1471-2407-10-509|title = Hyperbolastic modeling of tumor growth with a combined treatment of iodoacetate and dimethylsulphoxide|year = 2010|last1 = Eby|first1 = Wayne M.|last2 = Tabatabai|first2 = Mohammad A.|last3 = Bursac|first3 = Zoran|journal = BMC Cancer|volume = 10|pages = 509|pmid = 20863400|pmc = 2955040}}</ref>\n\nIn animal science, the hyperbolastic functions have been used for modeling broiler chicken growth.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.3382/ps.2007-00086|title = Hyperbolastic Models as a New Powerful Tool to Describe Broiler Growth Kinetics|year = 2007|last1 = Ahmadi|first1 = H.|last2 = Mottaghitalab|first2 = M.|journal = Poultry Science|volume = 86|issue = 11|pages = 2461\u20132465|pmid = 17954598}}</ref> The hyperbolastic model of type III was used to determine the size of the recovering wound.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1155/2014/965036| title=Novel Real-Time Facial Wound Recovery Synthesis Using Subsurface Scattering| year=2014| last1=Choi| first1=Taeyoung| last2=Chin| first2=Seongah| journal=The Scientific World Journal| volume=2014| pages=1\u20138| pmid=25197721| pmc=4146479}}</ref>\n\nIn the area of wound healing, the hyperbolastic models produced explicit functions accurately representing the time course of healing. Such functions have been used to investigate variations in the healing velocity among different kinds of wounds and at different stages in the healing process taking into consideration the areas of trace elements, growth factors, diabetic wounds, and nutrition.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1016/j.mcm.2010.10.013|title = Hyperbolastic modeling of wound healing|year = 2011|last1 = Tabatabai|first1 = M.A.|last2 = Eby|first2 = W.M.|last3 = Singh|first3 = K.P.|journal = Mathematical and Computer Modelling|volume = 53|issue = 5\u20136|pages = 755\u2013768}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/s41598-019-52523-9| title=Physicochemically Tuned Myofibroblasts for Wound Healing Strategy| year=2019| last1=Ko| first1=Ung Hyun| last2=Choi| first2=Jongjin| last3=Choung| first3=Jinseung| last4=Moon| first4=Sunghwan| last5=Shin| first5=Jennifer H.| journal=Scientific Reports| volume=9| issue=1| pages=16070| pmid=31690789| pmc=6831678| bibcode=2019NatSR...916070K}}</ref>\n\nAnother application of hyperbolastic functions is in the area of the [[stochastic diffusion]] process, whose mean function is a hyperbolastic curve of type I. The main characteristics of the process are studied and the maximum likelihood estimation for the parameters of the process is considered. To this end, the firefly metaheuristic optimization algorithm is applied after bounding the parametric space by a stage wise procedure. Some examples based on simulated sample paths and real data illustrate this development. A sample path of a diffusion process models the trajectory of a particle embedded in a flowing fluid and subjected to random displacements due to collisions with other particles, which is called Brownian motion.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1016/j.biosystems.2017.11.001|title = A hyperbolastic type-I diffusion process: Parameter estimation by means of the firefly algorithm|year = 2018|last1 = Barrera|first1 = Antonio|last2 = Rom\u00e1n-Rom\u00e1n|first2 = Patricia|last3 = Torres-Ruiz|first3 = Francisco|journal = Biosystems|volume = 163|pages = 11\u201322|pmid = 29129822}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3934/mbe.2020043| title=Hyperbolastic type-III diffusion process: Obtaining from the generalized Weibull diffusion process| year=2020| last1=Barrera| first1=Antonio| last2=Rom\u00e1n-Ro\u00e1n| first2=Patricia| last3=Torres-Ruiz| first3=Francisco| journal=Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering| volume=17| issue=1| pages=814\u2013833| pmid=31731379}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3390/math8020155| title=Two Stochastic Differential Equations for Modeling Oscillabolastic-Type Behavior| year=2020| last1=Barrera| first1=Antonio| last2=Rom\u00e1n-Rom\u00e1n| first2=Patricia| last3=Torres-Ruiz| first3=Francisco| journal=Mathematics| volume=8| issue=2| pages=155}}</ref> The hyperbolastic function of type III was used to model the proliferation of both adult mesenchymal and embryonic stem cells;<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s11517-010-0686-y| title=Mathematical modeling of stem cell proliferation| year=2011| last1=Tabatabai| first1=Mohammad A.| last2=Bursac| first2=Zoran| last3=Eby| first3=Wayne M.| last4=Singh| first4=Karan P.| journal=Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing| volume=49| issue=3| pages=253\u2013262| pmid=20953843}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1007/978-94-017-8032-2_18|chapter = Methods in Mathematical Modeling for Stem Cells|title = Therapeutic Applications in Disease and Injury |series = Stem Cells and Cancer Stem Cells|year = 2014|last1 = Eby|first1 = Wayne M.|last2 = Tabatabai|first2 = Mohammad A.|volume = 12|pages = 201\u2013217|isbn = 978-94-017-8031-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s42452-020-2070-3| title=The recent advances in the mathematical modelling of human pluripotent stem cells| year=2020| last1=Wadkin| first1=L. E.| last2=Orozco-Fuentes| first2=S.| last3=Neganova| first3=I.| last4=Lako| first4=M.| last5=Shukurov| first5=A.| last6=Parker| first6=N. G.| journal=SN Applied Sciences| volume=2| issue=2}}</ref> and, the hyperbolastic mixed model of type II has been used in modeling cervical cancer data.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0107242|title = Disparities in Cervical Cancer Mortality Rates as Determined by the Longitudinal Hyperbolastic Mixed-Effects Type II Model|year = 2014|last1 = Tabatabai|first1 = Mohammad A.|last2 = Kengwoung-Keumo|first2 = Jean-Jacques|last3 = Eby|first3 = Wayne M.|last4 = Bae|first4 = Sejong|last5 = Guemmegne|first5 = Juliette T.|last6 = Manne|first6 = Upender|last7 = Fouad|first7 = Mona|last8 = Partridge|first8 = Edward E.|last9 = Singh|first9 = Karan P.|journal = PLOS One|volume = 9|issue = 9|pages = e107242|pmid = 25226583|pmc = 4167327|bibcode = 2014PLoSO...9j7242T}}</ref> Hyperbolastic curves can be an important tool in analyzing cellular growth, the fitting of biological curves, and the growth of phytoplankton.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1471-2105-14-283|title = BGFit: Management and automated fitting of biological growth curves|year = 2013|last1 = Ver\u00edssimo|first1 = Andr\u00e9|last2 = Paix\u00e3o|first2 = Laura|last3 = Neves|first3 = Ana|last4 = Vinga|first4 = Susana|journal = BMC Bioinformatics|volume = 14|pages = 283|pmid = 24067087|pmc = 3848918}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.3934/mbe.2013.10.913|title = A flexible multivariable model for Phytoplankton growth|journal = Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering|year = 2013|volume = 10|issue = 3|pages = 913\u2013923|pmid = 23906155|last1 = Tabatabai|first1 = M. A.|last2 = Eby|first2 = W. M.|last3 = Bae|first3 = S.|last4 = Singh|first4 = K. P.}}</ref>\n\nIn forest ecology and management, the hyperbolastic models have been applied to model the relationship between DBH and height.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2017.04.015| title=A new nonlinear model applied to the height-DBH relationship in Gmelina arborea| year=2017| last1=Eby| first1=Wayne M.| last2=Oyamakin| first2=Samuel O.| last3=Chukwu| first3=Angela U.| journal=Forest Ecology and Management| volume=397| pages=139\u2013149}}</ref>\n\nThe multivariable ''hyperbolastic model type III'' has been used to analyze the growth dynamics of phytoplankton taking into consideration the concentration of nutrients.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3934/mbe.2013.10.913| title=A flexible multivariable model for Phytoplankton growth| journal=Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering| year=2013| volume=10| issue=3| pages=913\u2013923| pmid=23906155| last1=Tabatabai| first1=M. A.| last2=Eby| first2=W. M.| last3=Bae| first3=S.| last4=Singh| first4=K. P.}}</ref>\n\n==Hyperbolastic regressions==\n'''Hyperbolastic regressions''' are statistical models that utilize standard '''hyperbolatic functions''' to model a dichotomous outcome variable. The purpose of binary regression is to predict a binary outcome (dependent) variable using a set of explanatory (independent) variables. Binary regression is routinely used in many areas including medical, public health, dental, and biomedical sciences. Binary regression analysis was used to predict endoscopic lesions in iron deficiency anemia.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1471-230X-8-52|title = Predictors of gastrointestinal lesions on endoscopy in iron deficiency anemia without gastrointestinal symptoms|year = 2008|last1 = Majid|first1 = Shahid|last2 = Salih|first2 = Mohammad|last3 = Wasaya|first3 = Rozina|last4 = Jafri|first4 = Wasim|journal = BMC Gastroenterology|volume = 8|pages = 52|pmid = 18992171|pmc = 2613391}}</ref> In addition, binary regression was applied to differentiate between malignant and benign adnexal mass prior to surgery.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1200/JCO.2005.01.7632|title = Logistic Regression Model to Distinguish Between the Benign and Malignant Adnexal Mass Before Surgery: A Multicenter Study by the International Ovarian Tumor Analysis Group|year = 2005|last1 = Timmerman|first1 = Dirk|last2 = Testa|first2 = Antonia C.|last3 = Bourne|first3 = Tom|last4 = Ferrazzi|first4 = Enrico|last5 = Ameye|first5 = Lieveke|last6 = Konstantinovic|first6 = Maja L.|last7 = Van Calster|first7 = Ben|last8 = Collins|first8 = William P.|last9 = Vergote|first9 = Ignace|last10 = Van Huffel|first10 = Sabine|last11 = Valentin|first11 = Lil|journal = Journal of Clinical Oncology|volume = 23|issue = 34|pages = 8794\u20138801|pmid = 16314639}}</ref>\n\n===The hyperbolastic regression of type I===\nLet <math>Y</math> be a binary outcome variable which can assume one of two mutually exclusive values, success or failure. If we code success as <math>Y=1</math> and failure as <math>Y=0</math>, the hyperbolastic success probability of type I as a function of <math>K</math> explanatory variables <math>X_1,\\ X_2,\\ldots ,\\ X_k</math> is given by:\n\n:<math>P(Y=1)=\\frac{1}{1+e^{-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots+\\beta_k x_k)-\\operatorname{arcsinh}(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2 + \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k) } }</math>,\n\t\t\t\t\nwhere <math>\\beta_0,\\beta_1,\\ldots,\\beta_k</math> are model parameters. The odds of success is the ratio of probability of success to the probability of failure. For hyperbolastic regression of type I, the odds of success is denoted by <math>Odds_{H1}</math> and expressed by the equation:\n\n:<math>Odds_{H1}=e^{-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots+\\beta_k x_k)-\\operatorname{arcsinh}(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1+\\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k) }</math>.\n\nThe logarithm of <math>Odds_H1</math> is called the logit of Hyperbolastic of type I. The logit transformation is denoted by <math>L_{H1}</math> and can be written as:\n\n:<math>L_{H1}=\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1+\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots+\\beta_k x_k +\\operatorname{arcsinh}(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1+\\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k ) </math>.\n\n===The hyperbolastic regression of type II===\nFor the binary outcome variable <math>Y</math>, the hyperbolastic success probability of type II as a function of <math>K</math> explanatory variables <math>X_1, X_2,\\ldots, X_k</math> is:\n\n:<math> P(Y=1) = \\frac{1}{1 + \\operatorname{arcsinh}(e^{ - (\\beta_0 + \\beta_1 x_1+ \\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k) })} </math> ,\t\t\n\nFor the hyperbolastic regression of type II, the odds of success is denoted by <math>Odds_{H2}</math> and is given by:\n\n:<math>Odds_{H2} = \\frac{1}{\\operatorname{arcsinh}(e^{-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots +\\beta_k x_k ) } ) }. </math>\n\nThe logit transformation is denoted by <math> L_{H2} </math> and is given by:\n\n:<math>L_{H2}= - \\log{( \\operatorname{arcsinh} e^{\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots +\\beta_k x_k})}</math>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical models]]\n[[Category:Population models]]\n[[Category:Special functions]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Figure 1 - Hyperbolastic Type I.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type I function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 2 - Hyperbolastic Type I.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type I function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 3 - Hyperbolastic Type II.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type II function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 4 - Hyperbolastic Type II.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type II function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 5 - Hyperbolastic Type III.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic Type III function with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 6 - Hyperbolastic Type III.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic cumulative distribution function of type III with varying parameter values.]]\n[[File:Figure 7 - Hyperbolastic Type III.png|thumb|Graphic describing the Hyperbolastic probability density function of type III with varying parameter values.]]\n\nThe '''hyperbolastic functions''' are [[Function (mathematics)|mathematical functions]] that are used in medical [[statistical modeling]]. These models were originally developed to capture the growth dynamics of multicellular tumor spheres, and were introduced in 2005 by Mohammad Tabatabai, David Williams, and Zoran Bursac<ref name=\"Tabatabai 2005\">{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1742-4682-2-14 |year = 2005 |last1 = Tabatabai |first1 = Mohammad |last2 = Williams |first2 = David |last3 = Bursac |first3 = Zoran |title = Hyperbolastic growth models: Theory and application |journal = Theoretical Biology and Medical Modelling |volume = 2 |pages = 14 |pmid = 15799781 |pmc = 1084364}}</ref> The precision of hyperbolastic functions in modeling real world problems is somewhat due to their flexibility in their point of inflection.<ref name=\"Tabatabai 2005\" /> These functions can be used in a wide variety of modeling problems such as tumor growth, stem cell proliferation, pharma kinetics, cancer growth, sigmoid activation function in neural networks, and epidemiological disease progression or regression.<ref name=\"Tabatabai 2005\" />\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic functions'' can model both growth and decay curves until it reaches carrying capacity. Due to their flexibility, \nthese models have diverse applications in the medical field, with the ability to capture disease progression with an intervening\ntreatment. As the figures indicate, the ''hyperbolastic functions'' can fit a sigmoidal curve indicating that the slowest rate occurs at \nthe early and late stages. In addition to the presenting sigmoidal shapes, it can also accommodate biphasic situations where medical  \ninterventions slow or reverse disease progression; but, when the effect of the treatment vanishes, the disease will begin the \nsecond phase of it's progression until it reaches it's horizontal asymptote. \n\nOne of the main characteristics these functions have is that they cannot only fit sigmoidal shapes, but can also model biphasic growth patterns that other classical sigmoidal curves cannot adequately model. This distinguishing feature has advantageous applications in various fields including medicine, biology, economics, and engineering.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1099/mic.0.25880-0|title = Biphasic kinetics of growth and bacteriocin production with Lactobacillus amylovorus DCE 471 occur under stress conditions|year = 2003|last1 = Neysens|first1 = Patricia|last2 = Messens|first2 = Winy|last3 = Gevers|first3 = Dirk|last4 = Swings|first4 = Jean|last5 = De Vuyst|first5 = Luc|journal = Microbiology|volume = 149|issue = 4|pages = 1073\u20131082|pmid = 12686649}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Chu |first=Charlene |last2=Han |first2=Christina  |last3=Shimizu |first3=Hiromi  |last4=Wong |first4=Bonnie  |title=The Effect of Fructose, Galactose, and Glucose on the Induction of \u03b2-Galactosidase in ''Escherichia coli'' |url=https://www.microbiology.ubc.ca/sites/default/files/roles/drupal_ungrad/JEMI/2/2-1.pdf |year=2002 |journal=Journal of Experimental Microbiology and Immunology |volume=2 |pages=1\u20135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3934/mbe.2013.10.925| title=T model of growth and its application in systems of tumor-immunedynamics| journal=Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering| year=2013| volume=10| issue=3| pages=925\u2013938| pmid=23906156| last1=Tabatabai| first1=M. A.| last2=Eby| first2=W. M.| last3=Singh| first3=K. P.| last4=Bae| first4=S.| pmc=4476034}}</ref>\n\n=== Function H1 ===\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic rate equation of type I'', denoted H1, is given by:\n\n<math display =\"block\">\\frac{dP(x)}{dx}= \\frac{P(x)}{M} \\left(M-P \\left(x\\right)\\right)\\left(\\delta+\\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}\\right),</math>\n\nwhere <math>x</math> is any real number and \n<math>P\\left(x \\right)</math> is the population size at <math>x</math>. The parameter <math>M</math> represents carrying capacity, and parameters <math>\\delta</math> and <math>\\theta</math> jointly represent growth rate. The parameter <math>\\theta</math> gives the distance from a symmetric sigmoidal curve. Solving the hyperbolastic rate equation of type I for <math>P \\left(x \\right)</math> gives:\n\n<math display =\"block\">P(x)= \\frac{M}{1+ \\alpha e^{-\\delta x- \\theta \\operatorname{arsinh}(x)}},</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\operatorname{arsinh}</math> is the inverse hyperbolic sine function. If one desires to use the initial condition <math>P\\left(x_0\\right)=P_0</math>, then <math>\\alpha</math> can be expressed as:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\frac{M-P_0}{P_0} e^{\\delta x_0+ \\theta \\operatorname{arsinh}(x_0)}</math>.\n\nIf <math>x_0=0</math>, then <math>\\alpha</math> reduces to: \n\n:<math>\\alpha= \\frac{M-P_0}{P_0}</math>.\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic function of type I'' generalizes the [[logistic function]]. If the parameters <math>\\theta = 0</math>, then it would become a logistic function. This function <math>P(x)</math> is a ''hyperbolastic function of type I''. The ''standard hyperbolastic function of type I'' is \n\n:<math>P(x)= \\frac{1}{1+ e^{-x- \\operatorname{arsinh}(x)}}</math>.\n\n=== Function H2 ===\n\nThe ''hyperbolastic rate equation of type II'', denoted by H2, is defined as:\n\n:<math>\\frac{dP(x)}{dx}= \\frac{\\alpha \\delta \\gamma P^2 (x) x^{\\gamma - 1}}{M} \\tanh \\left(\\frac{M-P(x)}{\\alpha P(x)}\\right),</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\tanh</math> is the hyperbolic tangent function, <math>M</math> is the carrying capacity, and both <math>\\delta</math> and <math>\\gamma>0</math> jointly determine the growth rate. In addition, the parameter <math>\\gamma</math> represents acceleration in the time course. Solving the hyperbolastic rate function of type II for <math>P\\left(x\\right)</math> gives:\n\n:<math>P(x)=\\frac{M}{1+\\alpha\\operatorname{arsinh} \\left(e^{-\\delta x^\\gamma}\\right)}\n</math>.\n\nIf one desires to use initial condition <math>\nP(x_0)=P_0,</math> then <math>\\alpha</math> can be expressed as:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\frac{M-P_0}{P_0 \\operatorname{arsinh} \\left(e^{-\\delta x_0^\\gamma}\\right)}\n</math>.\n\nIf <math>x_0=0</math>, then <math>\\alpha</math> reduces to: \n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\frac{M-P_0}{P_0 \\operatorname{arsinh} (1)}</math>.\n\nThe ''standard hyperbolastic function of type II'' is defined as:\n\n:<math>P(x)=\\frac{1}{1+ \\operatorname{arsinh} \\left(e^{-x}\\right)}\n</math>.\n\n=== Function H3 ===\n\nThe hyperbolastic rate equation of type III is denoted by H3 and has the form:\n\n:<math>\\frac{dP(t)}{dt}= \\left(M-P \\left(t \\right)\\right)\\left(\\delta \\gamma t^{\\gamma - 1}+ \\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+ \\theta^2 t^2}}\\right)</math>,\n\nwhere <math>t</math> > 0. The parameter <math>M</math> represents the carrying capacity, and the parameters <math>\\delta,</math> <math>\\gamma,</math> and <math>\\theta</math> jointly determine the growth rate. The parameter <math>\\gamma,</math> represents acceleration of the time scale, while the size of <math>\\theta</math> represents distance from a symmetric sigmoidal curve. The solution to the differential equation of type III is: \n\n:<math>P(t)= M- \\alpha e^{-\\delta t^\\gamma- \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta t)}</math>,\n\nwith the initial condition <math>\nP\\left(t_0\\right)=P_0</math> we can express <math>\\alpha</math> as:\n\n:<math>\\alpha=\\left(M-P_0 \\right) e^{\\delta t_0^\\gamma+ \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta t_0)}</math>.\n\nThe standard hyperbolastic of type III is defined as:\n\n:<math>P\\left(t\\right)=1-e^{-t- \\operatorname{arsinh}(t)}</math>.\n\nThe hyperbolastic distribution of type III is a three-parameter family of continuous probability distributions with scale parameters <math>\\delta</math> > 0, and <math>\\theta</math> \u2265 0 and parameter <math>\\gamma</math> as the shape parameter. When the parameter <math>\\theta</math> = 0, the hyperbolastic distribution of type III is reduced to the Weibull distribution. The hyperbolastic cumulative distribution function is given by:\n\n:<math>F(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta)=\n\\begin{cases}\n1- e^{-\\delta x^\\gamma - \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta x)} & x\\geq0 ,\\\\\n0 & x < 0\n\\end{cases}\n</math>,\n\nand its corresponding probability density function is: \n\n:<math>\nf(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta) =\n\\begin{cases}\ne^{- \\delta x^\\gamma - \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta x)}\\left(\\delta \\gamma x^{\\gamma-1}+ \\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+\\theta^2 x^2}}\\right) & x\\geq0 ,\\\\\n0 & x<0\n\\end{cases}</math>.\n\nThe hazard function <math>h</math> (or failure rate) is given by: \n\n:<math>h\\left(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta \\right) = \\delta\\gamma x^{\\gamma-1} + \\frac{\\theta}{\\sqrt{1+ x^2\\theta^2}}.</math>\n\nThe survival function <math>S</math> is given by:\n\n:<math>S(x; \\delta, \\gamma, \\theta)= e^{- \\delta x^\\gamma- \\operatorname{arsinh}(\\theta x)}.</math>\n\n===Properties===\n\nIf one desires to calculate the point <math>x</math> where the population reaches a percentage of it's carrying capacity <math>M</math>, then \none can solve the equation:\n:<math>P(x) = k M</math> \nfor <math>x</math>, where <math>0 < k < 1</math>. For instance, the half point can be found by setting <math>k= \\frac{1}{2}</math>.\n\n===Applications===\n\nAccording to stem cell researchers at McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine at the University of Pittsburgh, \"a newer model [called the hyperbolastic type III or] H3 is a differential equation that also describes the cell growth. This model allows for much more variation and has been proven to better predict growth.\"<ref>{{cite document |vauthors=Roehrs T, Bogdan P, Gharaibeh B, et al. |date=n.d. |title=Proliferative heterogeneity in stem cell populations |url=https://www.engineering.pitt.edu/Departments/Bioengineering/_Documents/Undergraduate-research/Intramural-Internships/(2131)---Fall2012/Abstract_Roehrs |publisher=Live Cell Imaging Laboratory, McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine}}</ref>\n\nThe hyperbolastic growth models H1, H2, and H3 have been applied to analyze the growth of solid [[Ehrlich carcinoma]] using a variety of treatments.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1471-2407-10-509|title = Hyperbolastic modeling of tumor growth with a combined treatment of iodoacetate and dimethylsulphoxide|year = 2010|last1 = Eby|first1 = Wayne M.|last2 = Tabatabai|first2 = Mohammad A.|last3 = Bursac|first3 = Zoran|journal = BMC Cancer|volume = 10|pages = 509|pmid = 20863400|pmc = 2955040}}</ref>\n\nIn animal science, the hyperbolastic functions have been used for modeling broiler chicken growth.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.3382/ps.2007-00086|title = Hyperbolastic Models as a New Powerful Tool to Describe Broiler Growth Kinetics|year = 2007|last1 = Ahmadi|first1 = H.|last2 = Mottaghitalab|first2 = M.|journal = Poultry Science|volume = 86|issue = 11|pages = 2461\u20132465|pmid = 17954598}}</ref> The hyperbolastic model of type III was used to determine the size of the recovering wound.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1155/2014/965036| title=Novel Real-Time Facial Wound Recovery Synthesis Using Subsurface Scattering| year=2014| last1=Choi| first1=Taeyoung| last2=Chin| first2=Seongah| journal=The Scientific World Journal| volume=2014| pages=1\u20138| pmid=25197721| pmc=4146479}}</ref>\n\nIn the area of wound healing, the hyperbolastic models produced explicit functions accurately representing the time course of healing. Such functions have been used to investigate variations in the healing velocity among different kinds of wounds and at different stages in the healing process taking into consideration the areas of trace elements, growth factors, diabetic wounds, and nutrition.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1016/j.mcm.2010.10.013|title = Hyperbolastic modeling of wound healing|year = 2011|last1 = Tabatabai|first1 = M.A.|last2 = Eby|first2 = W.M.|last3 = Singh|first3 = K.P.|journal = Mathematical and Computer Modelling|volume = 53|issue = 5\u20136|pages = 755\u2013768}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/s41598-019-52523-9| title=Physicochemically Tuned Myofibroblasts for Wound Healing Strategy| year=2019| last1=Ko| first1=Ung Hyun| last2=Choi| first2=Jongjin| last3=Choung| first3=Jinseung| last4=Moon| first4=Sunghwan| last5=Shin| first5=Jennifer H.| journal=Scientific Reports| volume=9| issue=1| pages=16070| pmid=31690789| pmc=6831678| bibcode=2019NatSR...916070K}}</ref>\n\nAnother application of hyperbolastic functions is in the area of the [[stochastic diffusion]] process, whose mean function is a hyperbolastic curve of type I. The main characteristics of the process are studied and the maximum likelihood estimation for the parameters of the process is considered. To this end, the firefly metaheuristic optimization algorithm is applied after bounding the parametric space by a stage wise procedure. Some examples based on simulated sample paths and real data illustrate this development. A sample path of a diffusion process models the trajectory of a particle embedded in a flowing fluid and subjected to random displacements due to collisions with other particles, which is called Brownian motion.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1016/j.biosystems.2017.11.001|title = A hyperbolastic type-I diffusion process: Parameter estimation by means of the firefly algorithm|year = 2018|last1 = Barrera|first1 = Antonio|last2 = Rom\u00e1n-Rom\u00e1n|first2 = Patricia|last3 = Torres-Ruiz|first3 = Francisco|journal = Biosystems|volume = 163|pages = 11\u201322|pmid = 29129822}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3934/mbe.2020043| title=Hyperbolastic type-III diffusion process: Obtaining from the generalized Weibull diffusion process| year=2020| last1=Barrera| first1=Antonio| last2=Rom\u00e1n-Ro\u00e1n| first2=Patricia| last3=Torres-Ruiz| first3=Francisco| journal=Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering| volume=17| issue=1| pages=814\u2013833| pmid=31731379}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3390/math8020155| title=Two Stochastic Differential Equations for Modeling Oscillabolastic-Type Behavior| year=2020| last1=Barrera| first1=Antonio| last2=Rom\u00e1n-Rom\u00e1n| first2=Patricia| last3=Torres-Ruiz| first3=Francisco| journal=Mathematics| volume=8| issue=2| pages=155}}</ref> The hyperbolastic function of type III was used to model the proliferation of both adult mesenchymal and embryonic stem cells;<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s11517-010-0686-y| title=Mathematical modeling of stem cell proliferation| year=2011| last1=Tabatabai| first1=Mohammad A.| last2=Bursac| first2=Zoran| last3=Eby| first3=Wayne M.| last4=Singh| first4=Karan P.| journal=Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing| volume=49| issue=3| pages=253\u2013262| pmid=20953843}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1007/978-94-017-8032-2_18|chapter = Methods in Mathematical Modeling for Stem Cells|title = Therapeutic Applications in Disease and Injury |series = Stem Cells and Cancer Stem Cells|year = 2014|last1 = Eby|first1 = Wayne M.|last2 = Tabatabai|first2 = Mohammad A.|volume = 12|pages = 201\u2013217|isbn = 978-94-017-8031-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s42452-020-2070-3| title=The recent advances in the mathematical modelling of human pluripotent stem cells| year=2020| last1=Wadkin| first1=L. E.| last2=Orozco-Fuentes| first2=S.| last3=Neganova| first3=I.| last4=Lako| first4=M.| last5=Shukurov| first5=A.| last6=Parker| first6=N. G.| journal=SN Applied Sciences| volume=2| issue=2}}</ref> and, the hyperbolastic mixed model of type II has been used in modeling cervical cancer data.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0107242|title = Disparities in Cervical Cancer Mortality Rates as Determined by the Longitudinal Hyperbolastic Mixed-Effects Type II Model|year = 2014|last1 = Tabatabai|first1 = Mohammad A.|last2 = Kengwoung-Keumo|first2 = Jean-Jacques|last3 = Eby|first3 = Wayne M.|last4 = Bae|first4 = Sejong|last5 = Guemmegne|first5 = Juliette T.|last6 = Manne|first6 = Upender|last7 = Fouad|first7 = Mona|last8 = Partridge|first8 = Edward E.|last9 = Singh|first9 = Karan P.|journal = PLOS One|volume = 9|issue = 9|pages = e107242|pmid = 25226583|pmc = 4167327|bibcode = 2014PLoSO...9j7242T}}</ref> Hyperbolastic curves can be an important tool in analyzing cellular growth, the fitting of biological curves, and the growth of phytoplankton.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1471-2105-14-283|title = BGFit: Management and automated fitting of biological growth curves|year = 2013|last1 = Ver\u00edssimo|first1 = Andr\u00e9|last2 = Paix\u00e3o|first2 = Laura|last3 = Neves|first3 = Ana|last4 = Vinga|first4 = Susana|journal = BMC Bioinformatics|volume = 14|pages = 283|pmid = 24067087|pmc = 3848918}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.3934/mbe.2013.10.913|title = A flexible multivariable model for Phytoplankton growth|journal = Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering|year = 2013|volume = 10|issue = 3|pages = 913\u2013923|pmid = 23906155|last1 = Tabatabai|first1 = M. A.|last2 = Eby|first2 = W. M.|last3 = Bae|first3 = S.|last4 = Singh|first4 = K. P.}}</ref> \n\nIn forest ecology and management, the hyperbolastic models have been applied to model the relationship between DBH and height.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2017.04.015| title=A new nonlinear model applied to the height-DBH relationship in Gmelina arborea| year=2017| last1=Eby| first1=Wayne M.| last2=Oyamakin| first2=Samuel O.| last3=Chukwu| first3=Angela U.| journal=Forest Ecology and Management| volume=397| pages=139\u2013149}}</ref>\n\nThe multivariable ''hyperbolastic model type III'' has been used to analyze the growth dynamics of phytoplankton taking into consideration the concentration of nutrients.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.3934/mbe.2013.10.913| title=A flexible multivariable model for Phytoplankton growth| journal=Mathematical Biosciences and Engineering| year=2013| volume=10| issue=3| pages=913\u2013923| pmid=23906155| last1=Tabatabai| first1=M. A.| last2=Eby| first2=W. M.| last3=Bae| first3=S.| last4=Singh| first4=K. P.}}</ref>\n\n==Hyperbolastic regressions==\n'''Hyperbolastic regressions''' are statistical models that utilize standard '''hyperbolatic functions''' to model a dichotomous outcome variable. The purpose of binary regression is to predict a binary outcome (dependent) variable using a set of explanatory (independent) variables. Binary regression is routinely used in many areas including medical, public health, dental, and biomedical sciences. Binary regression analysis was used to predict endoscopic lesions in iron deficiency anemia.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/1471-230X-8-52|title = Predictors of gastrointestinal lesions on endoscopy in iron deficiency anemia without gastrointestinal symptoms|year = 2008|last1 = Majid|first1 = Shahid|last2 = Salih|first2 = Mohammad|last3 = Wasaya|first3 = Rozina|last4 = Jafri|first4 = Wasim|journal = BMC Gastroenterology|volume = 8|pages = 52|pmid = 18992171|pmc = 2613391}}</ref> In addition, binary regression was applied to differentiate between malignant and benign adnexal mass prior to surgery.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1200/JCO.2005.01.7632|title = Logistic Regression Model to Distinguish Between the Benign and Malignant Adnexal Mass Before Surgery: A Multicenter Study by the International Ovarian Tumor Analysis Group|year = 2005|last1 = Timmerman|first1 = Dirk|last2 = Testa|first2 = Antonia C.|last3 = Bourne|first3 = Tom|last4 = Ferrazzi|first4 = Enrico|last5 = Ameye|first5 = Lieveke|last6 = Konstantinovic|first6 = Maja L.|last7 = Van Calster|first7 = Ben|last8 = Collins|first8 = William P.|last9 = Vergote|first9 = Ignace|last10 = Van Huffel|first10 = Sabine|last11 = Valentin|first11 = Lil|journal = Journal of Clinical Oncology|volume = 23|issue = 34|pages = 8794\u20138801|pmid = 16314639}}</ref> \n\n===The hyperbolastic regression of type I===\nLet <math>Y</math> be a binary outcome variable which can assume one of two mutually exclusive values, success or failure. If we code success as <math>Y=1</math> and failure as <math>Y=0</math>, the hyperbolastic success probability of type I as a function of <math>K</math> explanatory variables <math>X_1,\\ X_2,\\ldots ,\\ X_k</math> is given by:\n\n:<math>P(Y=1)=\\frac{1}{1+e^{-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots+\\beta_k x_k)-\\operatorname{arcsinh}(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2 + \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k) } }</math>,\n\t\t\t\t\nwhere <math>\\beta_0,\\beta_1,\\ldots,\\beta_k</math> are model parameters. The odds of success is the ratio of probability of success to the probability of failure. For hyperbolastic regression of type I, the odds of success is denoted by <math>Odds_{H1}</math> and expressed by the equation:\n\n:<math>Odds_{H1}=e^{-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots+\\beta_k x_k)-\\operatorname{arcsinh}(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1+\\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k) }</math>.\n\nThe logarithm of <math>Odds_H1</math> is called the logit of Hyperbolastic of type I. The logit transformation is denoted by <math>L_{H1}</math> and can be written as:\n\n:<math>L_{H1}=\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1+\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots+\\beta_k x_k +\\operatorname{arcsinh}(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1+\\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k ) </math>.  \n\n===The hyperbolastic regression of type II===\nFor the binary outcome variable <math>Y</math>, the hyperbolastic success probability of type II as a function of <math>K</math> explanatory variables <math>X_1, X_2,\\ldots, X_k</math> is:\n\n:<math> P(Y=1) = \\frac{1}{1 + \\operatorname{arcsinh}(e^{ - (\\beta_0 + \\beta_1 x_1+ \\beta_2 x_2+ \\ldots +\\beta_k x_k) })} </math> ,\t\t\n\nFor the hyperbolastic regression of type II, the odds of success is denoted by <math>Odds_{H2}</math> and is given by: \n\n:<math>Odds_{H2} = \\frac{1}{\\operatorname{arcsinh}(e^{-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots +\\beta_k x_k ) } ) }. </math>\n\nThe logit transformation is denoted by <math> L_{H2} </math> and is given by:\n\n:<math>L_{H2}= - \\log{( \\operatorname{arcsinh} e^{\\beta_0+\\beta_1 x_1 +\\beta_2 x_2+\\ldots +\\beta_k x_k})}</math>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical models]]\n[[Category:Population models]]\n[[Category:Special functions]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolastic_functions"}
{"title_page": "1831 in literature", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1831|literature|poetry}}\nThis article presents lists of the literary events and publications in '''1831'''.\n\n==Events==\n*[[January 1]] \u2013 [[William Lloyd Garrison]] begins publication of the ''[[The Liberator (anti-slavery newspaper)|Liberator]]'', an abolitionist periodical in the United States.\n*[[February 18]] (old style) \u2013 [[Alexander Pushkin]] marries [[Natalia Pushkina|Natalya Goncharova]] at the [[Great Ascension Church]] on Bolshaya Nikitskaya Street in Moscow.\n*[[March 16]] \u2013 [[Victor Hugo]]'s historical [[Romanticism|romantic]] [[Gothic fiction|Gothic novel]] ''Notre-Dame de Paris'', known in English as ''[[The Hunchback of Notre-Dame]]'' (completed on January 15), is published by Gosselin in Paris.\n*[[March 19]] \u2013 The play ''La Cocarde Tricolore'' by the [[Cogniard brothers]] introduces the term \"''chauvinism''\".<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/cocarde-tricolore-episode-de-la-guerre-dalger-vaudeville-en-trois-actes/oclc/040505210 WorldCat entry]</ref>\n*[[April 18]] \u2013 ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' is first published.\n''Undated''\n*Convict [[Henry Savery]]'s [[Biography in literature|autobiographical fiction]] ''Quintus Servinton: a tale founded upon incidents of real occurrence'' is published anonymously in [[Tasmania]], the first Australian novel.<ref>{{citation |title=The development of Australian literature in the 19th century |url=http://courses.u3anet.org.au/wp-content/uploads/Language%20and%20Literature/Australian%20literature%20in%20the%2019th%20century.pdf |publisher=[[University of the Third Age]] |page=4 |accessdate=2013-08-22}}</ref>\n*Playwright [[Manuel Bret\u00f3n de los Herreros]] publishes a translation of [[Tibullus]], which secures him an appointment as sub-librarian at the Spanish national library ([[Biblioteca Nacional de Espa\u00f1a|Biblioteca P\u00fablica de Palacio]]).\n*[[Daniel Appleton]] publishes his first book in [[New York City]], so originating of the firm of [[D. Appleton & Company]].\n\n==New books==\n===Fiction===\n*[[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]]\n**''[[La Peau de chagrin]]''\n**''[[Sarrasine]]''\n**''[[Le Chef-d'\u0153uvre inconnu]]''\n*John Brownlow \u2013 ''Hans Sloane: a tale''\n*[[Selina Davenport]] \u2013 ''The Queen's Page''\n*[[Benjamin Disraeli]] \u2013 ''The Young Duke''\n*[[Susan Edmonstone Ferrier]] \u2013 ''Destiny''\n*[[Nikolai Gogol]] \u2013 ''[[Evenings on a Farm Near Dikanka]]''\n*[[Catherine Gore]]\n**''Mothers and Daughters''<ref name=QDL>{{cite book|first=Q. D.|last=Leavis|authorlink=Q. D. Leavis|title=Fiction and the Reading Public|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=Chatto & Windus|year=1965}}</ref>\n**''Pin Money''<ref name=QDL/>\n**''The School for Coquettes''\n**''[[The Tuileries]]''\n*[[Ann Hatton]] \u2013 ''Gerald Fitzgerald''\n*[[Victor Hugo]] \u2013 ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame]] (Notre Dame de Paris)''\n*[[Thomas Love Peacock]] \u2013 ''[[Crotchet Castle]]''\n*[[George Sand]] (as Amantine Aurore Dupin) and [[Jules Sandeau]] (as J. Sand) \u2013 ''Rose et Blanche''\n*[[Mary Shelley]] \u2013 ''[[Frankenstein]]'' (revised 1-volume edition)\n\n===Children===\n*[[Anne Knight (children's writer)|Anne Knight]] \u2013 ''Mary Gray. A tale for little girls''\n\n===Drama===\n*[[Robert Montgomery Bird]] \u2013 ''Gladiator''\n*[[Manuel Bret\u00f3n de los Herreros]] \u2013 ''Marcela o \u00bfCu\u00e1l de las tres?''\n*[[Dulduityn Danzanravjaa]] \u2013 ''Saran kh\u00f6kh\u00f6\u00f6'' (Moon Cuckoo; approximate date)\n*[[Alfred de Vigny]] \u2013 ''La Mar\u00e9chale d'Ancre''\n*[[Franz Grillparzer]] \u2013 ''Des Meeres und der Liebe Wellen'' (Waves of the Sea and of Love)\n*[[Victor Hugo]] \u2013 ''[[Marion Delorme (Hugo)|Marion Delorme]]''\n*[[Alexander Pushkin]] \u2013 ''[[Boris Godunov (play)|Boris Godunov]]'' (\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043d\u043e\u0432, published)\n*[[John Augustus Stone]] \u2013 ''[[Tancred, King of Sicily (play)|Tancred, King of Sicily]]''\n*[[Robert Taylor (Radical)|Robert Taylor]] \u2013 ''Swing, or, Who Are the Incendiaries?''\n\n===Poetry===\n*[[Thomas Hood]] \u2013 ''The Dream of [[Eugene Aram]], the Murderer''\n*[[Giacomo Leopardi]] \u2013 ''Canti''\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe]] \u2013 ''Poems''\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*[[Sir John Barrow, 1st Baronet]] \u2013 [[The Eventful History of the Mutiny and Piratical Seizure of HMS Bounty|''The Eventful History of the Mutiny and Piratical Seizure of HMS ''Bounty'': Its Cause and Consequences'']]\n*[[Washington Irving]] \u2013 ''Voyages and Discoveries of the Companions of Columbus''\n*[[John Stuart Mill]] \u2013 ''The Spirit of the Age''\n*[[James Cowles Prichard]] \u2013 ''Eastern Origin of the Celtic Nations''\n*[[Mary Prince]] \u2013 ''The History of Mary Prince, A West Indian Slave''\n\n==Births==\n*[[January 2]] \u2013 [[Justin Winsor]], American historian and librarian (died [[1897 in literature|1897]])\n*[[January 3]] \u2013 [[George Manville Fenn]], English novelist and educationalist (died [[1909 in literature|1909]])\n*[[January 14]] \u2013 [[John Cordy Jeaffreson]], English novelist and non-fiction writer (died [[1901 in literature|1901]])\n*[[February 25]] \u2013 [[Jane G. Austin]], American writer (died [[1894 in literature|1894]])\n*[[January 26]] \u2013 [[Mary Mapes Dodge]], American children's writer (died [[1907 in literature|1907]])\n*[[February 16]] \u2013 [[Nikolai Leskov]], Russian novelist and playwright (died [[1895 in literature|1895]])\n*[[March 29]] \u2013 [[Amelia Edith Huddleston Barr]], English novelist and teacher (died [[1919 in literature|1919]])\n*[[April 9]] \u2013 [[Clara Harrison Stranahan]], American author and college founder (died [[1905 in literature|1905]])\n*[[April 19]] \u2013 [[Mary Louise Booth]], American writer, editor, and translator (died [[1889 in literature|1889]])\n*[[May 6]] \u2013 [[Mary C. Ames]], American writer (died [[1884 in literature|1884]])\n*[[June 7]] \u2013 [[Amelia Edwards]], English fiction writer and Egyptologist (died [[1892 in literature|1892]])\n*[[June 25]] \u2013 [[Harriet Mann Miller]], American author, naturalist, and ornithologist (died [[1918 in literature|1918]])\n*[[July 3]] \u2013 [[Edmund Yates]], Scottish writer (died [[1894 in literature|1894]])\n*[[July 7]] \u2013 [[Jane Elizabeth Conklin]], American religious writer and poet (died [[1914 in literature|1914]])\n*[[August 1]] \u2013 [[William Aldis Wright]], English writer and literary editor (died [[1914 in literature|1914]])\n*[[September 5]] \u2013 [[Victorien Sardou]], French dramatist (died [[1908 in literature|1908]])\n*[[September 12]] \u2013 [[\u00c1lvares de Azevedo]], Brazilian [[Ultra-Romanticism|Ultra-Romantic]] writer (died [[1852 in literature|1852]])\n*[[October 7]] \u2013 [[Eleanor Kirk]], American writer (died [[1908 in literature|1908]])\n*[[October 15]] \u2013 [[Helen Hunt Jackson]], American poet, writer and activist (died [[1885 in literature|1885]])\n*''Undated'' \u2013 [[Nora Perry (writer)|Nora Perry]], American writer (died [[1896 in literature|1896]])\n\n==Deaths==\n*[[January 2]] \u2013 [[Barthold Georg Niebuhr]], Danish-born German historian (born [[1776 in literature|1776]])\n*[[January 14]] \u2013 [[Henry Mackenzie]], Scottish novelist (born [[1745 in literature|1745]])\n*[[January 21]] \u2013 [[Ludwig Achim von Arnim]], German poet and novelist (heart attack, born [[1781 in literature|1781]])\n*[[February 25]] \u2013 [[Friedrich Maximilian Klinger]], German dramatist and novelist, originator of ''[[Sturm und Drang]]'' (born [[1752 in literature|1752]])<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ayres |first1=H.M. |title=The Reader's Dictionary of Authors |date=1917 |publisher=Warner Library Co. |location=New York |url=https://www.bartleby.com/library/bios/3515.html |accessdate=24 March 2019 |chapter=Friedrich Maximilian von Klinger (1752\u20131831)}}</ref>\n*[[April 4]] \u2013 [[Isaiah Thomas (publisher)|Isaiah Thomas]], American publisher (born [[1749 in literature|1749]])\n*[[June 30]] \u2013 [[William Roscoe]], English poet (born [[1753 in literature|1753]])\n*[[September 12]] \u2013 [[Jippensha Ikku]] (\u5341\u8fd4\u820e \u4e00\u4e5d), Japanese novelist and humorist (born [[1765 in literature|1765]])\n*[[October 2]] \u2013 [[Jos\u00e9 Agostinho de Macedo]], Portuguese poet (born [[1761 in literature|1761]])\n*[[December 18]] \u2013 [[Willem Bilderdijk]], Dutch author (born [[1756 in literature|1756]])\n*[[December 26]] \u2013 [[Henry Louis Vivian Derozio]], Indian poet and teacher (born [[1809 in literature|1809]])\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Chancellor's Gold Medal]] \u2013 [[George Stovin Venables]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Year in literature article categories}}\n[[Category:1831 books| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year nav topic5|1831|literature|poetry}}\nThis article presents lists of the literary events and publications in '''1831'''.\n\n==Events==\n*[[January 1]] \u2013 [[William Lloyd Garrison]] begins publication of the ''[[The Liberator (anti-slavery newspaper)|Liberator]]'', an abolitionist periodical in the United States.\n*[[February 18]] (old style) \u2013 [[Alexander Pushkin]] marries [[Natalia Pushkina|Natalya Goncharova]] at the [[Great Ascension Church]] on Bolshaya Nikitskaya Street in Moscow.\n*[[March 16]] \u2013 [[Victor Hugo]]'s historical [[Romanticism|romantic]] [[Gothic fiction|Gothic novel]] ''Notre-Dame de Paris'', known in English as ''[[The Hunchback of Notre-Dame]]'' (completed on January 15), is published by Gosselin in Paris.\n*[[March 19]] \u2013 The play ''La Cocarde Tricolore'' by the [[Cogniard brothers]] introduces the term \"''chauvinism''\".<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/cocarde-tricolore-episode-de-la-guerre-dalger-vaudeville-en-trois-actes/oclc/040505210 WorldCat entry]</ref>\n*[[April 18]] \u2013 ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' is first published.\n*Convict [[Henry Savery]]'s [[Biography in literature|autobiographical fiction]] ''Quintus Servinton: a tale founded upon incidents of real occurrence'' is published anonymously in [[Tasmania]], the first Australian novel.<ref>{{citation |title=The development of Australian literature in the 19th century |url=http://courses.u3anet.org.au/wp-content/uploads/Language%20and%20Literature/Australian%20literature%20in%20the%2019th%20century.pdf |publisher=[[University of the Third Age]] |page=4 |accessdate=2013-08-22}}</ref>\n\n''Uncertain dates''\n*Playwright [[Manuel Bret\u00f3n de los Herreros]] publishes a translation of [[Tibullus]], which secures him an appointment as sub-librarian at the Spanish national library ([[Biblioteca Nacional de Espa\u00f1a|Biblioteca P\u00fablica de Palacio]]).\n*[[Daniel Appleton]] publishes his first book in [[New York City]], so originating of the firm of [[D. Appleton & Company]].\n\n==New books==\n===Fiction===\n*[[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]]\n**''[[La Peau de chagrin]]''\n**''[[Sarrasine]]''\n**''[[Le Chef-d'\u0153uvre inconnu]]''\n*John Brownlow \u2013 ''Hans Sloane: a tale''\n*[[Selina Davenport]] \u2013 ''The Queen's Page''\n*[[Benjamin Disraeli]] \u2013 ''The Young Duke''\n*[[Susan Edmonstone Ferrier]] \u2013 ''Destiny''\n*[[Nikolai Gogol]] \u2013 ''[[Evenings on a Farm Near Dikanka]]''\n*[[Catherine Gore]]\n**''Mothers and Daughters''<ref name=QDL>{{cite book|first=Q. D.|last=Leavis|authorlink=Q. D. Leavis|title=Fiction and the Reading Public|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=Chatto & Windus|year=1965}}</ref>\n**''Pin Money''<ref name=QDL/>\n**''The School for Coquettes''\n**''[[The Tuileries]]''\n*[[Ann Hatton]] \u2013 ''Gerald Fitzgerald''\n*[[Victor Hugo]] \u2013 ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame]] (Notre Dame de Paris)''\n*[[Thomas Love Peacock]] \u2013 ''[[Crotchet Castle]]''\n*[[George Sand]] (as Amantine Aurore Dupin) and [[Jules Sandeau]] (as J. Sand) \u2013 ''Rose et Blanche''\n*[[Mary Shelley]] \u2013 ''[[Frankenstein]]'' (revised 1-volume edition)\n\n===Children===\n*[[Anne Knight (children's writer)|Anne Knight]] \u2013 ''Mary Gray. A tale for little girls''\n\n===Drama===\n*[[Robert Montgomery Bird]] \u2013 ''Gladiator''\n*[[Manuel Bret\u00f3n de los Herreros]] \u2013 ''Marcela o \u00bfCu\u00e1l de las tres?''\n*[[Dulduityn Danzanravjaa]] \u2013 ''Saran kh\u00f6kh\u00f6\u00f6'' (Moon Cuckoo; approximate date)\n*[[Alfred de Vigny]] \u2013 ''La Mar\u00e9chale d'Ancre''\n*[[Franz Grillparzer]] \u2013 ''Des Meeres und der Liebe Wellen'' (Waves of the Sea and of Love)\n*[[Victor Hugo]] \u2013 ''[[Marion Delorme (Hugo)|Marion Delorme]]''\n*[[Alexander Pushkin]] \u2013 ''[[Boris Godunov (play)|Boris Godunov]]'' (\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043d\u043e\u0432, published)\n*[[John Augustus Stone]] \u2013 ''[[Tancred, King of Sicily (play)|Tancred, King of Sicily]]''\n*[[Robert Taylor (Radical)|Robert Taylor]] \u2013 ''Swing, or, Who Are the Incendiaries?''\n\n===Poetry===\n*[[Thomas Hood]] \u2013 ''The Dream of [[Eugene Aram]], the Murderer''\n*[[Giacomo Leopardi]] \u2013 ''Canti''\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe]] \u2013 ''Poems''\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*[[Sir John Barrow, 1st Baronet]] \u2013 [[The Eventful History of the Mutiny and Piratical Seizure of HMS Bounty|''The Eventful History of the Mutiny and Piratical Seizure of HMS ''Bounty'': Its Cause and Consequences'']]\n*[[Washington Irving]] \u2013 ''Voyages and Discoveries of the Companions of Columbus''\n*[[John Stuart Mill]] \u2013 ''The Spirit of the Age''\n*[[James Cowles Prichard]] \u2013 ''Eastern Origin of the Celtic Nations''\n*[[Mary Prince]] \u2013 ''The History of Mary Prince, A West Indian Slave''\n\n==Births==\n*[[January 2]] \u2013 [[Justin Winsor]], American historian and librarian (died [[1897 in literature|1897]])\n*[[January 3]] \u2013 [[George Manville Fenn]], English novelist and educationalist (died [[1909 in literature|1909]])\n*[[January 14]] \u2013 [[John Cordy Jeaffreson]], English novelist and non-fiction writer (died [[1901 in literature|1901]])\n*[[February 25]] \u2013 [[Jane G. Austin]], American writer (died [[1894 in literature|1894]])\n*[[January 26]] \u2013 [[Mary Mapes Dodge]], American children's writer (died [[1907 in literature|1907]])\n*[[February 16]] \u2013 [[Nikolai Leskov]], Russian novelist and playwright (died [[1895 in literature|1895]])\n*[[March 29]] \u2013 [[Amelia Edith Huddleston Barr]], English novelist and teacher (died [[1919 in literature|1919]])\n*[[April 9]] \u2013 [[Clara Harrison Stranahan]], American author and college founder (died [[1905 in literature|1905]])\n*[[April 19]] \u2013 [[Mary Louise Booth]], American writer, editor, and translator (died [[1889 in literature|1889]])\n*[[May 6]] \u2013 [[Mary C. Ames]], American writer (died [[1884 in literature|1884]])\n*[[June 7]] \u2013 [[Amelia Edwards]], English fiction writer and Egyptologist (died [[1892 in literature|1892]])\n*[[June 25]] \u2013 [[Harriet Mann Miller]], American author, naturalist, and ornithologist (died [[1918 in literature|1918]])\n*[[July 3]] \u2013 [[Edmund Yates]], Scottish writer (died [[1894 in literature|1894]])\n*[[July 7]] \u2013 [[Jane Elizabeth Conklin]], American religious writer and poet (died [[1914 in literature|1914]])\n*[[August 1]] \u2013 [[William Aldis Wright]], English writer and literary editor (died [[1914 in literature|1914]])\n*[[September 5]] \u2013 [[Victorien Sardou]], French dramatist (died [[1908 in literature|1908]])\n*[[September 12]] \u2013 [[\u00c1lvares de Azevedo]], Brazilian [[Ultra-Romanticism|Ultra-Romantic]] writer (died [[1852 in literature|1852]])\n*[[October 7]] \u2013 [[Eleanor Kirk]], American writer (died [[1908 in literature|1908]])\n*[[October 15]] \u2013 [[Helen Hunt Jackson]], American poet, writer and activist (died [[1885 in literature|1885]])\n\n''Uncertain date''\n*[[Nora Perry (writer)|Nora Perry]], American writer (died [[1896 in literature|1896]])\n\n==Deaths==\n*[[January 2]] \u2013 [[Barthold Georg Niebuhr]], Danish-born German historian (born [[1776 in literature|1776]])\n*[[January 14]] \u2013 [[Henry Mackenzie]], Scottish novelist (born [[1745 in literature|1745]])\n*[[January 21]] \u2013 [[Ludwig Achim von Arnim]], German poet and novelist (heart attack, born [[1781 in literature|1781]])\n*[[February 25]] \u2013 [[Friedrich Maximilian Klinger]], German dramatist and novelist, originator of ''[[Sturm und Drang]]'' (born [[1752 in literature|1752]])<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ayres |first1=H.M. |title=The Reader's Dictionary of Authors |date=1917 |publisher=Warner Library Co. |location=New York |url=https://www.bartleby.com/library/bios/3515.html |accessdate=24 March 2019 |chapter=Friedrich Maximilian von Klinger (1752\u20131831)}}</ref>\n*[[April 4]] \u2013 [[Isaiah Thomas (publisher)|Isaiah Thomas]], American publisher (born [[1749 in literature|1749]])\n*[[June 30]] \u2013 [[William Roscoe]], English poet (born [[1753 in literature|1753]])\n*[[September 12]] \u2013 [[Jippensha Ikku]] (\u5341\u8fd4\u820e \u4e00\u4e5d), Japanese novelist and humorist (born [[1765 in literature|1765]])\n*[[October 2]] \u2013 [[Jos\u00e9 Agostinho de Macedo]], Portuguese poet (born [[1761 in literature|1761]])\n*[[December 18]] \u2013 [[Willem Bilderdijk]], Dutch author (born [[1756 in literature|1756]])\n*[[December 26]] \u2013 [[Henry Louis Vivian Derozio]], Indian poet and teacher (born [[1809 in literature|1809]])\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Chancellor's Gold Medal]] \u2013 [[George Stovin Venables]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Year in literature article categories}}\n[[Category:1831 books| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in literature]]\n", "name_user": "Camboxer", "label": "safe", "comment": "subheadings moved", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1831_in_literature"}
{"title_page": "Bangladesh Development Bank", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Bangladesh Development Bank Limited\n| logo = Bangladesh_Development_Bank_Limited_LOGO.png\n| type = [[National bank|State owned bank]]\n| Extent of Shareholding = 100% share owned by the Government of Bangladesh\n| num_locations    = 46\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list | Mohammad Mejbahuddin ([[Chairman]]) | kazi Alamgir([[Managing Director|MD]])}}\n| industry = [[International financial institutions|Development Bank]]<br />[[Bank]]<br />[[Capital Markets]] and allied industries\n| products = [[Retail banking]], [[Private banking]], [[Commercial bank|Corporate Banking]], [[Deposit (finance)|Deposits]], [[Mortgage loan]], Savings Scheme, Sanchay Scheme, Trade and Retail Forex\n| revenue = \n| net_income = \n| assets = {{BDTConvert|54.55|b|lk=yes}}\n| num_employees = About 775\n| foundation = [[Dhaka]], 16 November 2009\n| location = |\n| homepage = {{URL|www.bdbl.com.bd}}\n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh Development Bank''' (Bengali: \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09a1\u09c7\u09ad\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09ae\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u0982\u0995 \u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf\u099f\u09c7\u09a1,\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09ac\u09bf\u098f\u09b2) is a [[List of banks in Bangladesh#Specialized banks|state owned specialized commercial bank]] in [[Bangladesh]]. The bank came into effect with the merger of ailing [[Bangladesh Shilpa Bank Bhaban|Bangladesh Shilpa Bank]] and Shilpa Rin Sangstha, which were established in 1972 to provide loans and facilities to industrial units, help set up new industries and expand investment in Bangladesh.<ref name=\"ds\">{{cite news |title=Development Bank takes off |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=120388 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BDBL Bhabhan.jpg|thumb|BDBL Bhaban, 8 Rajuk Avenue, Dhaka 1000,Head Office, [[Dhaka]].]]\n\n== History ==\nBangladesh Development Bank was established on 16 November 2009 as a Public Limited Company by merging the state owned Bangladesh Shilpa Bank and Bangladesh Shilpa Rin Sangstha, both which were established on 31 October 1972.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|title=BDBL {{!}} Objectives|website=www.bdbl.com.bd|access-date=2019-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907142513/http://bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|archive-date=2014-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-116999|title=Bangladesh Development Bank starts journey Jan 3|date=2009-12-08|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank started in 2010 with 534 court cases concerning 21 billion taka and 24.6 billion taka in written off liabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-120388|title=Development Bank takes off|date=2010-01-04|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe bank has had issues with loan defaulting, as of 2018, the total defaulted loans at the bank stood at 23.32 billion taka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/no-frills/news/over-two-lakh-privileged-institutions-1635121|title=A loan defaulting epidemic: Over two lakh privileged institutions!|date=2018-09-18|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> On 11 June 2019, the [[Anti-Corruption Commission (Bangladesh)|Anti-Corruption Commission]] sued for officials of the bank for allegedly  embezzling 250 million taka from the bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/4-bdbl-officials-used-embezzling-tk-25cr-1755547|title=4 BDBL officials sued for embezzling Tk 25cr|date=2019-06-11|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nThe bank now offers a variety of services - Commercial Banking; SME Banking;Developmental Banking etc.\n\n== Branches ==\nThere are currently 46 branches of BDBL banking across the country. The bank provides all kinds of commercial banking services to its customers through its 46 branch network in the country. The 46th branch of Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) has been inaugurated at Tamalatla Bazar in Bagatipar, Natore.<ref name=\"new branch open\">{{cite news |title=Mohammad Mejbahuddin, Chairman of Bangladesh Development Bank Ltd, inaugurating the bank's 46th branch at Bagatipara in Natore recently. Bank's Managing Director Kazi Alamgir, General Manager Md Abdul Baki and Deputy Commissioner Mohammad Shah Riaz, among others, were present.|url=http://m.thedailynewnation.com/news/240759/mohammad-mejbahuddin-chairman-of-bangladesh-development-bank-ltd-inaugurating-the-banks-46th-branch-at-bagatipara-in-natore-recently-banks-managing-director-kazi-alamgir-general-manager-md-abdul-baki-and-deputy-commissioner-mohammad-shah-riaz-among-others-were-present |newspaper=thedailynewnation |accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) operates online banking activities.BDBL SWIFT Code is BDDBBDDH\n\n== Technological Banking==\nCBS has begun on-line banking activities to control banking transactions as well as overall operations from the beginning of July 2015. Besides, all transactions are done through core banking software from any branch of BDBL, through Bangladesh Automated Check Clearing House (Batch). Inter-bank transactions of the kind are settled. Next is the inter-banking transaction across the country Under the Naden Bangladesh Electronic Funds Transfer Network (BEFTN) or 'Electronic Funds Transfer System', inter-bank electronic debit-credit transaction process is performed smoothly and fastest from any bank branch without any charges or fees at any time. Rapid and risk-free solutions using real time gross settlement (RTGS) From anywhere in the country amounts to one million or more to immediate payment. The fastest repayment of the inter-bank payment system is through RTGS. Customers and banks from anywhere in the world are able to make this transaction.\n\n== Management ==\nThe managing director controls the overall activities of the bank. The Managing Director is assisted by the General Manager and Department Heads working at the central office. Bank branch managers report the activities related to the matter directly to the managing director and to the department head. According to Article 95 of the Articles of Association of the Bank, there shall be a ten-member board of directors with the chairman as its chairman. The current chairman of the board of directors is former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.<ref name=\"new chairmen joined in bdbl\">{{cite news |title=Chairman of Board of Directors of BDBL and former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.|url=https://today.thefinancialexpress.com.bd/trade-market/chairman-of-board-of-directors-of-bdbl-and-former-senior-secretary-mohammad-mejbahuddin-1567358659?date=02-09-2019 |newspaper=the financial express | access-date=2019-09-02}} </ref>\n\n==Awards==\nBDBL also obtained Third Prize as the Best Corporate in the Banking Sector (State-owned Commercial Bank) given by The Institute of Cost and Management Accountants of Bangladesh (ICMAB) in its Best Corporate Award-2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=ICMAB Best Corporate Awards-2014|url=http://www.icmab.org.bd/event/best-corporate-awards-2014/|publisher=ICMAB|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Strengths & Challenges==\nOUR STRENGTHS-\n*Good Corporate Governance & Practices.\n*Sound and strong capital & asset base.\n*Deep focus on quality control.\n*A dedicated line of human resource.\n*Culture of internal control and compliance. \n\nOur BUSINESS CHALLENGES-\n*Intense competition in the domestic market\n*Global economic slowdown\n*Strict capital requirement under Basel \u2013 III\n*Sharp fall in the interest rates on deposit\n*Increasing Business Risk\nhttp://www.bdbl.com.bd/image/Annual%20Report/BDBL_Annual%20Report_2015.pdf\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bdbl.com.bd/ Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n{{Banks in Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Bangladesh Development Bank Limited\n| logo = Bangladesh_Development_Bank_Limited_LOGO.png\n| type = [[National bank|State owned bank]]\n| num_locations    = 46\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list | Mohammad Mejbahuddin ([[Chairman]]) | kazi Alamgir([[Managing Director|MD]])}}\n| industry = [[International financial institutions|Development Bank]]<br />[[Bank]]<br />[[Capital Markets]] and allied industries\n| products = [[Retail banking]], [[Private banking]], [[Commercial bank|Corporate Banking]], [[Deposit (finance)|Deposits]], [[Mortgage loan]], Savings Scheme, Sanchay Scheme, Trade and Retail Forex\n| revenue = \n| net_income = \n| assets = {{BDTConvert|54.55|b|lk=yes}}\n| num_employees = About 775\n| foundation = [[Dhaka]], 16 November 2009\n| location = |\n| homepage = {{URL|www.bdbl.com.bd}}\n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh Development Bank''' (Bengali: \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09a1\u09c7\u09ad\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09ae\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u0982\u0995 \u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf\u099f\u09c7\u09a1,\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09ac\u09bf\u098f\u09b2) is a [[List of banks in Bangladesh#Specialized banks|state owned specialized commercial bank]] in [[Bangladesh]]. The bank came into effect with the merger of ailing [[Bangladesh Shilpa Bank Bhaban|Bangladesh Shilpa Bank]] and Shilpa Rin Sangstha, which were established in 1972 to provide loans and facilities to industrial units, help set up new industries and expand investment in Bangladesh.<ref name=\"ds\">{{cite news |title=Development Bank takes off |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=120388 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BDBL Bhabhan.jpg|thumb|BDBL Bhaban, 8 Rajuk Avenue, Dhaka 1000,Head Office, [[Dhaka]].]]\n\n== History ==\nBangladesh Development Bank was established on 16 November 2009 as a Public Limited Company by merging the state owned Bangladesh Shilpa Bank and Bangladesh Shilpa Rin Sangstha, both which were established on 31 October 1972.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|title=BDBL {{!}} Objectives|website=www.bdbl.com.bd|access-date=2019-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907142513/http://bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|archive-date=2014-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-116999|title=Bangladesh Development Bank starts journey Jan 3|date=2009-12-08|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank started in 2010 with 534 court cases concerning 21 billion taka and 24.6 billion taka in written off liabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-120388|title=Development Bank takes off|date=2010-01-04|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe bank has had issues with loan defaulting, as of 2018, the total defaulted loans at the bank stood at 23.32 billion taka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/no-frills/news/over-two-lakh-privileged-institutions-1635121|title=A loan defaulting epidemic: Over two lakh privileged institutions!|date=2018-09-18|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> On 11 June 2019, the [[Anti-Corruption Commission (Bangladesh)|Anti-Corruption Commission]] sued for officials of the bank for allegedly  embezzling 250 million taka from the bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/4-bdbl-officials-used-embezzling-tk-25cr-1755547|title=4 BDBL officials sued for embezzling Tk 25cr|date=2019-06-11|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nThe bank now offers a variety of services - Commercial Banking; SME Banking;Developmental Banking etc.\n\n== Branches ==\nThere are currently 46 branches of BDBL banking across the country. The bank provides all kinds of commercial banking services to its customers through its 46 branch network in the country. The 46th branch of Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) has been inaugurated at Tamalatla Bazar in Bagatipar, Natore.<ref name=\"new branch open\">{{cite news |title=Mohammad Mejbahuddin, Chairman of Bangladesh Development Bank Ltd, inaugurating the bank's 46th branch at Bagatipara in Natore recently. Bank's Managing Director Kazi Alamgir, General Manager Md Abdul Baki and Deputy Commissioner Mohammad Shah Riaz, among others, were present.|url=http://m.thedailynewnation.com/news/240759/mohammad-mejbahuddin-chairman-of-bangladesh-development-bank-ltd-inaugurating-the-banks-46th-branch-at-bagatipara-in-natore-recently-banks-managing-director-kazi-alamgir-general-manager-md-abdul-baki-and-deputy-commissioner-mohammad-shah-riaz-among-others-were-present |newspaper=thedailynewnation |accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) operates online banking activities.BDBL SWIFT Code is BDDBBDDH\n\n== Technological Banking==\nCBS has begun on-line banking activities to control banking transactions as well as overall operations from the beginning of July 2015. Besides, all transactions are done through core banking software from any branch of BDBL, through Bangladesh Automated Check Clearing House (Batch). Inter-bank transactions of the kind are settled. Next is the inter-banking transaction across the country Under the Naden Bangladesh Electronic Funds Transfer Network (BEFTN) or 'Electronic Funds Transfer System', inter-bank electronic debit-credit transaction process is performed smoothly and fastest from any bank branch without any charges or fees at any time. Rapid and risk-free solutions using real time gross settlement (RTGS) From anywhere in the country amounts to one million or more to immediate payment. The fastest repayment of the inter-bank payment system is through RTGS. Customers and banks from anywhere in the world are able to make this transaction.\n\n== Management ==\nThe managing director controls the overall activities of the bank. The Managing Director is assisted by the General Manager and Department Heads working at the central office. Bank branch managers report the activities related to the matter directly to the managing director and to the department head. According to Article 95 of the Articles of Association of the Bank, there shall be a ten-member board of directors with the chairman as its chairman. The current chairman of the board of directors is former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.<ref name=\"new chairmen joined in bdbl\">{{cite news |title=Chairman of Board of Directors of BDBL and former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.|url=https://today.thefinancialexpress.com.bd/trade-market/chairman-of-board-of-directors-of-bdbl-and-former-senior-secretary-mohammad-mejbahuddin-1567358659?date=02-09-2019 |newspaper=the financial express | access-date=2019-09-02}} </ref>\n\n==Awards==\nBDBL also obtained Third Prize as the Best Corporate in the Banking Sector (State-owned Commercial Bank) given by The Institute of Cost and Management Accountants of Bangladesh (ICMAB) in its Best Corporate Award-2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=ICMAB Best Corporate Awards-2014|url=http://www.icmab.org.bd/event/best-corporate-awards-2014/|publisher=ICMAB|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bdbl.com.bd/ Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n{{Banks in Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Engr. Md. Nadimul Islam", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh_Development_Bank"}
{"title_page": "Varhadi dialect", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2015}}\n{{Ijvjnfobox language\n| name = Varhadi\n| altname = Varhadi\u2013Nagpuri\n| nativename = \u0935\u0931\u094d\u0939\u093e\u0921\u0940\n| states = [[India]]\n| region = [[Vidarbha]] region of [[States and Territories of India|Maharashtra]]; also southwestern [[Chhattisgarh]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]] and northern [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| speakers = 7.0 million\n| date = 1995\n| ref = e18\n| familycolor = Indo-European\n| fam2 = [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]\n| fam3 = [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]\n| fam4 = [[Southern Indo-Aryan languages|Southern Zone]]\n| fam5 = [[Marathi Language|Marathi]]\n| script = [[Devan\u0101gar\u012b|Devanagari]]<ref>Devanagari has been big bigger with LOVEpromulgated as the official script.</ref>\n| iso3 = vah\n| notice = Indic\n| glotto = varh1239\n| glottorefname = Varhadi-Nagpuri\n}}\n\n'''Varhadi''' is a dialect of [[Marathi language|Marathi]] spoken in [[Vidarbha]] region of [[Maharashtra]] and by [[Marathi people]] of adjoining parts of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Chhattisgarh]] and [[Andhra Pradesh|Telangana]] in [[India]].\n\n== Vocabulary and Grammar ==\n\nAlthough all the dialects of Marathi are mutually intelligible to one another up to a great extent, each dialect can be distinctly identified by its unique characteristics. Likewise, Varhadi replaces the case endings ''la'' (\u0932\u093e) & ''na'' (\u0928\u093e) of standard Marathi with ''le'' (\u0932\u0947), a feature it shares with neighboring [[Khandeshi]] [[dialect]]. So, ''mala'' (\u092e\u0932\u093e) (to me) of standard Marathi becomes ''male'' (\u092e\u0932\u0947) while ''tyanna'' (\u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0902\u0928\u093e) (to them) becomes ''tyahile'' (\u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u0947) in Varhadi. Despite being a dialect of Marathi, the vocabulary as well as grammar of Varhadi is significantly influenced by [[Hindi]] due proximity of Vidarbha to [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The common examples of Hindi words in Varhadi which are different than standard Marathi are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Varhadi !! Hindi !! Standard Marathi !! English\n|-\n| {{IAST| S\u012bdh\u0101}} (\u0938\u0940\u0927\u093e) || {{IAST| S\u012bdh\u0101}} (\u0938\u0940\u0927\u093e) || {{IAST|Sara\u1e37}} (\u0938\u0930\u0933) || Straight\n|-\n| {{IAST|Bud\u0101}} (\u092c\u0941\u0921\u093e ) || {{IAST|Buddh\u0101}} (\u092c\u0941\u0922\u094d\u0922\u093e) || {{IAST|Mh\u0101t\u0101r\u0101}} (\u092e\u094d\u0939\u093e\u0924\u093e\u0930\u093e) || Old man\n|-\n| {{IAST| Pagal\u0101}} (\u092a\u0917\u0932\u093e) || {{IAST| P\u0101gal}} (\u092a\u093e\u0917\u0932) || {{IAST|Ved\u0101}} (\u0935\u0947\u0921\u093e)  || Mad\n|-\n| {{IAST|A\u1e45g\u016br}} (\u0905\u0902\u0917\u0942\u0930) || {{IAST|A\u1e45g\u016br}} (\u0905\u0902\u0917\u0942\u0930) || {{IAST|Dr\u0101k\u015ba}} (\u0926\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0915\u094d\u0937) || Grapes\n|}\n\t\nThe grammatical changes in Varhadi differing from standard Marathi & closer to Hindi are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Varhadi !! Hindi !! Standard Marathi !! English\n|-\n| {{IAST|M\u012b j\u0101'un r\u0101hil\u014d}} (\u092e\u0940 \u091c\u093e\u0909\u0928 \u0930\u093e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u094b) || {{IAST|Mai\u1e41 j\u0101 rah\u0101 h\u016b\u1e41}} (\u092e\u0948\u0902 \u091c\u093e \u0930\u0939\u093e \u0939\u0942\u0902) || {{IAST|M\u012b z\u0101t\u014dy}} (\u092e\u0940 \u091c\u093e\u0924\u094b\u092f) || I am going\n|-\n| {{IAST|M\u012b \u0101l\u012b}} (\u092e\u0940 \u0906\u0932\u0940) || {{IAST|Mai\u1e41 \u0101y\u012b}} (\u092e\u0948\u0902 \u0906\u092f\u0940) || {{IAST|M\u012b \u0101l\u0113}} (\u092e\u0940 \u0906\u0932\u0947) || I (feminine) came\n|-\n| {{IAST|Tujh\u0101v\u0101l\u0101 p\u0113n d\u0113}} (\u0924\u0941\u091d\u093e\u0935\u093e\u0932\u093e \u092a\u0947\u0928 \u0926\u0947) || {{IAST|Apn\u0101 p\u0113n d\u014d}} (\u0905\u092a\u0928\u093e \u092a\u0947\u0928 \u0926\u094b ) ||{{IAST|Tuzh\u0101 p\u0113n d\u0113}} (\u0924\u0941\u091d\u0902 \u092a\u0947\u0928 \u0926\u0947) || Give your pen\n|-\n| {{IAST|P\u0101n\u012b gh\u0113\u016bn gh\u0113}} (\u092a\u093e\u0928\u0940 \u0918\u0947\u090a\u0928 \u0918\u0947) || {{IAST|P\u0101n\u012b l\u0113 l\u014d}} (\u092a\u093e\u0928\u0940 \u0932\u0947 \u0932\u094b) || {{IAST|P\u0101n\u012b gh\u0113}} (\u092a\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0918\u0947) || (Please) Have water.\n|}\nApart from this, there are many words & phrases indigenous to Varhadi i.e. common to neither standard Marathi nor Hindi. For instance, to give stress on a request or an order, suffix {{IAST|zo}} (\u091c\u094b) (singular)/ {{IAST|z\u0101}} (\u091c\u093e) (plural) is used like \"{{IAST|Mahya porichya lagnale ye za}} (\u092e\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092a\u094b\u0930\u0940\u091a\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0932\u0917\u094d\u0928\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092f\u0947\u091c\u093e ) \"Please attend my daughter\u2019s wedding.\" Also, there are words & phrases maintained by Varhadi which were present in older Marathi (spoken 300 years ago or even prior to that) and have vanished from mainstream Marathi. E.g., in vocative case, {{IAST|aga}} (\u0905\u0917\u093e) is said in Varhadi instead of \u2018''are''\u2019 (\u0905\u0930\u0947) of standard Marathi. Another good example is the sentence construction of past continuous tense e.g. in Varhadi, it is said \u2018''Tho bahu abhyas kare''\" (\u0925\u094b \u092c\u0939\u0942 \u0905\u092d\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0938 \u0915\u0930\u0947) (He studied a lot) unlike \"''To khup abhyas karaycha''\" (\u0924\u094b \u0916\u0942\u092a \u0905\u092d\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0938 \u0915\u0930\u093e\u092f\u091a\u093e) of standard Marathi.\n\nIn most of the [[Indo-Aryan languages]] (or even in [[Dravidian languages]], for that matter), Sanskritized words of standard language get simplified in spoken dialects. Exceptionally, Varhadi has a few [[Sanskrit]] ''[[tatsama]]'' words for whom the standard Marathi counterparts are modified words (''[[tadbhava]] shabda'') such as in eastern parts of Vidarbha, snake is called {{IAST|sarpa}} (\u0938\u0930\u094d\u092a) unlike {{IAST|s\u0101p}} (\u0938\u093e\u092a) of standard Marathi.\n\n\tThe forms of Varhadi vary in different parts of Vidarbha and also, as per castes. The influence of Hindi increases as one moves towards Madhya Pradesh. E.g. in the parts adjacent to Madhya Pradesh, \u2018''zana padte''\u2019 (\u091c\u093e\u0928\u0902 \u092a\u0921\u0924\u0947) (I have to go) is preferred over \u2018''zaa lagte''\u2019 (\u091c\u093e \u0932\u093e\u0917\u0924\u0947), which is similar to Hindi \u2018''jana padta hai''\u2019 (\u091c\u093e\u0928\u093e \u092a\u0921\u0924\u093e \u0939\u0948). Also, consonant \u2018''cha''\u2019 (\u091a) (like in ''chook'')(\u091a\u0942\u0915), prevalent in Marathi but absent in Hindi, is often pronounced as \u2018''cha''\u2019 like in ''vachan'' (\u0935\u091a\u0928). So, ''paach'' (\u092a\u093e\u091a) (five) may be pronounced as ''paanch'' of Hindi.\n\t\nIn the areas closer to [[Marathwada]] region of Maharashtra and on the contrary, distant to Madhya Pradesh, Varhadi is influenced by dialects of adjacent parts of Marathwada. One can easily recognize a person from Pusad, Digras or Umarkhed taluka of [[Yavatmal]] district by his sentence of present continuous tense. Somebody from this area will say \u2018''me mandirat zaylo''\u2019 (\u092e\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930\u093e\u0924 \u091c\u093e\u092f\u0932\u094b) (I am going to visit a temple) instead of \u2018''mee mandirat zaun rahilo''\u2019 (\u092e\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930\u093e\u0924 \u091c\u093e\u090a\u0928 \u0930\u093e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u094b) of other parts of Vidarbha. Similarly, the tone of speech in Chikhli, Mehkar, Deulgaonraja talukas of [[Buldana]] district is similar to that of nearby parts of Marathwada. If someone from this area speaks to a person from Nagpur or Wardha, the latter may get confused whether the former is from Vidarbha or Marathwada. Likewise, Khandeshi dialect spoken in parts of [[Jalgaon]] district adjacent to Vidarbha is too similar to be differentiated from Varhadi of [[Malkapur, Buldhana|Malkapur]]- [[Shegaon]] belt of Buldana district.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nagpur]]\n*[[Vidarbha]] [[Regions and Divisions of Maharashtra|region]] of [[Maharashtra]].\n*[[Maharashtra#Languages|Languages in Maharashtra]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Incubator|code=vah}}\n* [http://www.language-archives.org/language/vah \"Resources in and about the Varhadi-Nagpuri language\"]\n* [http://www.india9.com/i9show/Varhadi-50721.htm Varhadi at India9]\n* [http://devplw.library.upenn.edu/cgi-bin/sdi/vbook/browse?type=lcsubc&key=Varhadi-Nagpuri%20dialect%20--%20Dictionaries Varhadi Language in Penn Libraries]\n\n{{Languages of India}}\n\n[[Category:Southern Indo-Aryan languages]]\n[[Category:Indo-Aryan languages]]\n[[Category:Vidarbha]]\n[[Category:Marathi language]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox language\n| name = Varhadi\n| altname = Varhadi\u2013Nagpuri\n| nativename = \u0935\u0931\u094d\u0939\u093e\u0921\u0940\n| states = [[India]]\n| region = [[Vidarbha]] region of [[States and Territories of India|Maharashtra]]; also southwestern [[Chhattisgarh]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]] and northern [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| speakers = 7.0 million\n| date = 1995\n| ref = e18\n| familycolor = Indo-European\n| fam2 = [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]\n| fam3 = [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]\n| fam4 = [[Southern Indo-Aryan languages|Southern Zone]]\n| fam5 = [[Marathi Language|Marathi]]\n| script = [[Devan\u0101gar\u012b|Devanagari]]<ref>Devanagari has been big bigger with LOVEpromulgated as the official script.</ref>\n| iso3 = vah\n| notice = Indic\n| glotto = varh1239\n| glottorefname = Varhadi-Nagpuri\n}}\n\n'''Varhadi''' is a dialect of [[Marathi language|Marathi]] spoken in [[Vidarbha]] region of [[Maharashtra]] and by [[Marathi people]] of adjoining parts of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Chhattisgarh]] and [[Andhra Pradesh|Telangana]] in [[India]].\n\n== Vocabulary and Grammar ==\n\nAlthough all the dialects of Marathi are mutually intelligible to one another up to a great extent, each dialect can be distinctly identified by its unique characteristics. Likewise, Varhadi replaces the case endings ''la'' (\u0932\u093e) & ''na'' (\u0928\u093e) of standard Marathi with ''le'' (\u0932\u0947), a feature it shares with neighboring [[Khandeshi]] [[dialect]]. So, ''mala'' (\u092e\u0932\u093e) (to me) of standard Marathi becomes ''male'' (\u092e\u0932\u0947) while ''tyanna'' (\u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0902\u0928\u093e) (to them) becomes ''tyahile'' (\u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u0947) in Varhadi. Despite being a dialect of Marathi, the vocabulary as well as grammar of Varhadi is significantly influenced by [[Hindi]] due proximity of Vidarbha to [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The common examples of Hindi words in Varhadi which are different than standard Marathi are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Varhadi !! Hindi !! Standard Marathi !! English\n|-\n| {{IAST| S\u012bdh\u0101}} (\u0938\u0940\u0927\u093e) || {{IAST| S\u012bdh\u0101}} (\u0938\u0940\u0927\u093e) || {{IAST|Sara\u1e37}} (\u0938\u0930\u0933) || Straight\n|-\n| {{IAST|Bud\u0101}} (\u092c\u0941\u0921\u093e ) || {{IAST|Buddh\u0101}} (\u092c\u0941\u0922\u094d\u0922\u093e) || {{IAST|Mh\u0101t\u0101r\u0101}} (\u092e\u094d\u0939\u093e\u0924\u093e\u0930\u093e) || Old man\n|-\n| {{IAST| Pagal\u0101}} (\u092a\u0917\u0932\u093e) || {{IAST| P\u0101gal}} (\u092a\u093e\u0917\u0932) || {{IAST|Ved\u0101}} (\u0935\u0947\u0921\u093e)  || Mad\n|-\n| {{IAST|A\u1e45g\u016br}} (\u0905\u0902\u0917\u0942\u0930) || {{IAST|A\u1e45g\u016br}} (\u0905\u0902\u0917\u0942\u0930) || {{IAST|Dr\u0101k\u015ba}} (\u0926\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0915\u094d\u0937) || Grapes\n|}\n\t\nThe grammatical changes in Varhadi differing from standard Marathi & closer to Hindi are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Varhadi !! Hindi !! Standard Marathi !! English\n|-\n| {{IAST|M\u012b j\u0101'un r\u0101hil\u014d}} (\u092e\u0940 \u091c\u093e\u0909\u0928 \u0930\u093e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u094b) || {{IAST|Mai\u1e41 j\u0101 rah\u0101 h\u016b\u1e41}} (\u092e\u0948\u0902 \u091c\u093e \u0930\u0939\u093e \u0939\u0942\u0902) || {{IAST|M\u012b z\u0101t\u014dy}} (\u092e\u0940 \u091c\u093e\u0924\u094b\u092f) || I am going\n|-\n| {{IAST|M\u012b \u0101l\u012b}} (\u092e\u0940 \u0906\u0932\u0940) || {{IAST|Mai\u1e41 \u0101y\u012b}} (\u092e\u0948\u0902 \u0906\u092f\u0940) || {{IAST|M\u012b \u0101l\u0113}} (\u092e\u0940 \u0906\u0932\u0947) || I (feminine) came\n|-\n| {{IAST|Tujh\u0101v\u0101l\u0101 p\u0113n d\u0113}} (\u0924\u0941\u091d\u093e\u0935\u093e\u0932\u093e \u092a\u0947\u0928 \u0926\u0947) || {{IAST|Apn\u0101 p\u0113n d\u014d}} (\u0905\u092a\u0928\u093e \u092a\u0947\u0928 \u0926\u094b ) ||{{IAST|Tuzh\u0101 p\u0113n d\u0113}} (\u0924\u0941\u091d\u0902 \u092a\u0947\u0928 \u0926\u0947) || Give your pen\n|-\n| {{IAST|P\u0101n\u012b gh\u0113\u016bn gh\u0113}} (\u092a\u093e\u0928\u0940 \u0918\u0947\u090a\u0928 \u0918\u0947) || {{IAST|P\u0101n\u012b l\u0113 l\u014d}} (\u092a\u093e\u0928\u0940 \u0932\u0947 \u0932\u094b) || {{IAST|P\u0101n\u012b gh\u0113}} (\u092a\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0918\u0947) || (Please) Have water.\n|}\nApart from this, there are many words & phrases indigenous to Varhadi i.e. common to neither standard Marathi nor Hindi. For instance, to give stress on a request or an order, suffix {{IAST|zo}} (\u091c\u094b) (singular)/ {{IAST|z\u0101}} (\u091c\u093e) (plural) is used like \"{{IAST|Mahya porichya lagnale ye za}} (\u092e\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092a\u094b\u0930\u0940\u091a\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0932\u0917\u094d\u0928\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092f\u0947\u091c\u093e ) \"Please attend my daughter\u2019s wedding.\" Also, there are words & phrases maintained by Varhadi which were present in older Marathi (spoken 300 years ago or even prior to that) and have vanished from mainstream Marathi. E.g., in vocative case, {{IAST|aga}} (\u0905\u0917\u093e) is said in Varhadi instead of \u2018''are''\u2019 (\u0905\u0930\u0947) of standard Marathi. Another good example is the sentence construction of past continuous tense e.g. in Varhadi, it is said \u2018''Tho bahu abhyas kare''\" (\u0925\u094b \u092c\u0939\u0942 \u0905\u092d\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0938 \u0915\u0930\u0947) (He studied a lot) unlike \"''To khup abhyas karaycha''\" (\u0924\u094b \u0916\u0942\u092a \u0905\u092d\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0938 \u0915\u0930\u093e\u092f\u091a\u093e) of standard Marathi.\n\nIn most of the [[Indo-Aryan languages]] (or even in [[Dravidian languages]], for that matter), Sanskritized words of standard language get simplified in spoken dialects. Exceptionally, Varhadi has a few [[Sanskrit]] ''[[tatsama]]'' words for whom the standard Marathi counterparts are modified words (''[[tadbhava]] shabda'') such as in eastern parts of Vidarbha, snake is called {{IAST|sarpa}} (\u0938\u0930\u094d\u092a) unlike {{IAST|s\u0101p}} (\u0938\u093e\u092a) of standard Marathi.\n\n\tThe forms of Varhadi vary in different parts of Vidarbha and also, as per castes. The influence of Hindi increases as one moves towards Madhya Pradesh. E.g. in the parts adjacent to Madhya Pradesh, \u2018''zana padte''\u2019 (\u091c\u093e\u0928\u0902 \u092a\u0921\u0924\u0947) (I have to go) is preferred over \u2018''zaa lagte''\u2019 (\u091c\u093e \u0932\u093e\u0917\u0924\u0947), which is similar to Hindi \u2018''jana padta hai''\u2019 (\u091c\u093e\u0928\u093e \u092a\u0921\u0924\u093e \u0939\u0948). Also, consonant \u2018''cha''\u2019 (\u091a) (like in ''chook'')(\u091a\u0942\u0915), prevalent in Marathi but absent in Hindi, is often pronounced as \u2018''cha''\u2019 like in ''vachan'' (\u0935\u091a\u0928). So, ''paach'' (\u092a\u093e\u091a) (five) may be pronounced as ''paanch'' of Hindi.\n\t\nIn the areas closer to [[Marathwada]] region of Maharashtra and on the contrary, distant to Madhya Pradesh, Varhadi is influenced by dialects of adjacent parts of Marathwada. One can easily recognize a person from Pusad, Digras or Umarkhed taluka of [[Yavatmal]] district by his sentence of present continuous tense. Somebody from this area will say \u2018''me mandirat zaylo''\u2019 (\u092e\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930\u093e\u0924 \u091c\u093e\u092f\u0932\u094b) (I am going to visit a temple) instead of \u2018''mee mandirat zaun rahilo''\u2019 (\u092e\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930\u093e\u0924 \u091c\u093e\u090a\u0928 \u0930\u093e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u094b) of other parts of Vidarbha. Similarly, the tone of speech in Chikhli, Mehkar, Deulgaonraja talukas of [[Buldana]] district is similar to that of nearby parts of Marathwada. If someone from this area speaks to a person from Nagpur or Wardha, the latter may get confused whether the former is from Vidarbha or Marathwada. Likewise, Khandeshi dialect spoken in parts of [[Jalgaon]] district adjacent to Vidarbha is too similar to be differentiated from Varhadi of [[Malkapur, Buldhana|Malkapur]]- [[Shegaon]] belt of Buldana district.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nagpur]]\n*[[Vidarbha]] [[Regions and Divisions of Maharashtra|region]] of [[Maharashtra]].\n*[[Maharashtra#Languages|Languages in Maharashtra]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Incubator|code=vah}}\n* [http://www.language-archives.org/language/vah \"Resources in and about the Varhadi-Nagpuri language\"]\n* [http://www.india9.com/i9show/Varhadi-50721.htm Varhadi at India9]\n* [http://devplw.library.upenn.edu/cgi-bin/sdi/vbook/browse?type=lcsubc&key=Varhadi-Nagpuri%20dialect%20--%20Dictionaries Varhadi Language in Penn Libraries]\n\n{{Languages of India}}\n\n[[Category:Southern Indo-Aryan languages]]\n[[Category:Indo-Aryan languages]]\n[[Category:Vidarbha]]\n[[Category:Marathi language]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4042:208a:4389:a151:aeda:e45:6e0a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Varhadi_dialect"}
