. |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AstDys|5201}}\n* {{JPL small body}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Minor planets navigator |5200 Pamal |number=5201 |(5202) 1983 XX}}\n{{Small Solar System bodies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferraz-Mello}}\n[[Category:Background asteroids|005201]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by Edward L. G. Bowell]]\n[[Category:Minor planets named for people]]\n[[Category:Named minor planets]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1983|19831201]]\n\n\n{{beltasteroid-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AlanM1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move {Use dmy dates} above infobox, fix mdy dates,MOS:UNITSYMBOLS, infobox list templates, minor CE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/5201_Ferraz-Mello"}
{"title_page": "Tropical rainforest climate", "text_new": "[[File:Koppen-Geiger Map Af present.svg|thumb|right|upright=1.8|Worldwide zones of Tropical rainforest climate (Af).]]A '''tropical rainforest climate''' is a [[tropical climate]] usually found within 10 to 15 degrees latitude of the [[equator]], and has at least 60 mm of rainfall every month of the year. Regions with this climate are typically designated ''Af'' by the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. A tropical rainforest climate is typically hot, very weird and wet.\n\n==Description==\nTropical rain forests have a type of [[tropical climate]] in which there is no [[dry season]]&mdash;all months have an average [[precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] value of at least {{convert|60|mm|in|abbr=on}}. In rainforest climates the dry season is very short, and rainfall is normally heavy throughout the year. One day in a tropical rainforest climate can be very similar to the next, while the change in temperature between day and night may be larger than the average change in temperature during the year. <ref name=McKnight>{{Cite book \n| last1 = McKnight \n| first1 = Tom L \n| last2 = Hess \n| first2 = Darrel \n| year = 2000 \n| chapter = Climate Zones and Types \n| title = Physical Geography: A Landscape Appreciation \n| pages = [https://archive.org/details/physicalgeographmckn/page/205 205&ndash;8] \n| location = Upper Saddle River, NJ \n| publisher = Prentice Hall \n| isbn = 978-0-13-020263-5 \n| url = https://archive.org/details/physicalgeographmckn/page/205 \n}}</ref>\n\nWhen tropical rain forest climates are more dominated by the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] (ITCZ) than the trade winds (and with no or rare cyclones), so usually located near the equator, they are also called equatorial climates. Otherwise, when they are more dominated by the trade winds than the ITCZ, they are called tropical trade-wind climates. In pure equatorial climates, the atmospheric pressure is low, almost constant so the (horizontal) pressure gradient is low. Consequently the winds are rare and usually weak (except sea and land breezes in coastal areas) while in tropical trade-wind climates, often located at higher latitudes than the equatorial climates, wind is almost permanent which incidentally explains why rainforest formations are impoverished compared to those of equatorial climates due to their necessary resistance to strong winds accompanying tropical disturbances.<ref>Climatologie Pierre Estienne Alain Godard, pages 309 and 316</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Rainbow Jungle.jpg|thumb|upright=2.25|right|Upland rain forest in Borneo. Sabah, Malaysia]] A tropical rain forest climate is usually found at [[latitude]]s within 15 degrees North and South of the [[equator]], which are dominated by the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] (ITCZ). The climate is most commonly found in [[South America]], [[Central Africa]], [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Oceania]]. These rain forests are uniformly and monotonously wet throughout the year. Locations in [[Oceania]], areas along the  coast of [[South America|South]] and [[Central America]], from [[Ecuador]] to [[Belize]], parts of [[Central Africa]], and much of [[Indonesia]] have this type of climate.\n\n==Notable cities with tropical rain forest climates==\n<div float=\"left\">\n{{col-begin|width=70%}}\n{{col-1-of-2}}\n'''Africa'''\n* [[Moroni, Comoros|Moroni]], Comoros\n* [[Kisumu]], [[Kenya]]\n* [[Harper, Liberia|Harper]], [[Liberia]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Antalaha]], [[Madagascar]]\n* [[Manakara]], Madagascar\n* [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n\n'''Americas'''\n* [[Punta Gorda, Belize|Punta Gorda]], [[Belize]]\n* [[Lim\u00f3n]], [[Costa Rica]]\n* [[Hig\u00fcey (city)|Hig\u00fcey]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n* [[Puerto Barrios]], [[Guatemala]]\n* [[La Ceiba]], [[Honduras]]\n* [[Port Antonio]], [[Jamaica]]\n* [[Bluefields]], [[Nicaragua]]\n* [[Changuinola]], [[Panama]]\n* [[Bel\u00e9m]], [[Brazil]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Maca\u00e9]], Brazil\n* [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], Brazil\n* [[Florencia, Caquet\u00e1|Florencia]], [[Colombia]]\n* [[Medell\u00edn, Colombia|Medell\u00edn]], Colombia\n* [[Puyo, Pastaza|Puyo]], [[Ecuador]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni]], [[French Guiana]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Georgetown, Guyana|Georgetown]], [[Guyana]]\n* [[Iquitos]], [[Peru]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Paramaribo]], [[Suriname]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n\n{{col-2-of-2}}'''\n'''Asia'''\n* [[Bandar Seri Begawan]], [[Brunei]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Jayapura]], [[Indonesia]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Padang, Indonesia|Padang]], Indonesia ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Tangerang]], Indonesia ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Ishigaki, Okinawa|Ishigaki]], [[Japan]]\n* [[Johor Bahru]], [[Malaysia]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Kuching]], Malaysia ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Davao City]], [[Philippines]] ''(subequatorial climate)''\n* [[Polomolok]], Philippines ''(subequatorial climate)'' \n* [[Tacloban, Leyte]], Philippines\n* [[Singapore]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Kurunegala]], [[Sri Lanka]] \n* [[Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte]], Sri Lanka ''(subequatorial climate)'' \n* [[Hualien City|Hualien]], [[Taiwan]]\n* [[Orchid Island]], Taiwan\n* [[Nakhon Si Thammarat]], [[Thailand]]\n\n'''Oceania'''\n* [[Pago Pago]], [[American Samoa]]\n* [[Innisfail, Queensland|Innisfail]], [[Australia]]\n* [[Palikir]], [[Federated States of Micronesia]]\n* [[Suva]], [[Fiji]]\n* [[Tarawa]], [[Kiribati]] ''(subequatorial climate)'' \n* [[Majuro]], [[Marshall Islands]]\n* [[Tabubil]], [[Papua New Guinea]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Lae]], Papua New Guinea ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Apia]], [[Samoa]]\n* [[Honiara]], [[Solomon Islands]]\n* [[Nuku\u2019alofa]], [[Tonga]]\n* [[Funafuti]], [[Tuvalu]]\n* [[Hilo]], [[United States]]\n* [[Port Vila]], [[Vanuatu]]\n{{col-end}}\n</div>\n\n\n{{climate chart|[[Paramaribo|Paramaribo, Suriname]]\n|22|30|200\n|22|30|140\n|22|30|150\n|22|31|210\n|23|30|290\n|22|31|290\n|22|31|230\n|23|32|170\n|23|32|90\n|23|33|90\n|23|32|120\n|22|30|180\n|float=left\n|clear=none\n|source= [http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=52218&refer=&units=metric]\n}}\n\n{{climate chart|[[Mbandaka|Mbandaka, DR Congo]]\n|19|31|80\n|20|32|100\n|20|32|150\n|20|31|140\n|20|31|130\n|19|30|110\n|17|30|100\n|17|29|100\n|19|30|200\n|19|30|210\n|19|30|190\n|19|30|120\n|float=left\n|clear=none\n|source=[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=50046&refer=&units=metric]\n}}\n\n{{climate chart|[[Biak|Biak, Indonesia]]\n|25|29|250\n|25|28|240\n|25|29|250\n|25|29|200\n|25|29|250\n|25|29|230\n|25|28|250\n|25|29|240\n|25|29|220\n|25|29|180\n|25|30|190\n|25|29|230\n|float=left\n|clear=none\n|source= [http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=6579&refer=&units=metric]\n}}\n\n{{climate chart\n| [[Kuching, Malaysia]]\n|22.9|30.4|466.2\n|23.2|29.1|445.2\n|23.0|30.3|465.2\n|23.3|32.0|251.0\n|23.5|32.7|346.8\n|22.9|31.6|309.8\n|23.3|31.2|183.5\n|23.0|31.6|326.4\n|23.2|32.1|207.8\n|23.2|31.5|307.2\n|23.5|31.9|482.4\n|23.2|30.4|516.2\n|float  = left\n|clear  = none\n|source = Monthly Statistical Bulletin Sarawak<!--- source of the data --->\n}}\n\n{{climate chart\n| [[Quibd\u00f3|Quibd\u00f3, Colombia]]\n|23|30.1|579.3\n|23.1|30.2|505.4\n|23.2|30.4|526.1\n|23.4|30.8|654.6\n|23.2|31|776.2\n|23|31.2|761.6\n|22.8|31.1|802.6\n|22.9|31|851.7\n|22.8|30.7|702.4\n|22.7|30.4|654\n|22.8|30.2|728.1\n|23|29.6|588.5\n|maxprecip = 851.7\n|float = left\n|clear = 652652625\n|source = [http://bart.ideam.gov.co/cliciu/quibdo/tabla.htm]\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tropics]]\n*[[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Koppen}}\n\n[[Category:Climate]]\n[[Category:K\u00f6ppen climate classifications]]\n[[Category:Rainforests]]\n[[Category:Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests]]\n[[Category:Tropical rainforests]]\n[[Category:Tropics|Climate, Rainforest]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Koppen-Geiger Map Af present.svg|thumb|right|upright=1.8|Worldwide zones of Tropical rainforest climate (Af).]]A '''tropical rainforest climate''' is a [[tropical climate]] usually found within 10 to 15 degrees latitude of the [[equator]], and has at least 60 mm of rainfall every month of the year. Regions with this climate are typically designated ''Af'' by the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. A tropical rainforest climate is typically hot, very humid and wet.\n\n==Description==\nTropical rain forests have a type of [[tropical climate]] in which there is no [[dry season]]&mdash;all months have an average [[precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] value of at least {{convert|60|mm|in|abbr=on}}. In rainforest climates the dry season is very short, and rainfall is normally heavy throughout the year. One day in a tropical rainforest climate can be very similar to the next, while the change in temperature between day and night may be larger than the average change in temperature during the year. <ref name=McKnight>{{Cite book \n| last1 = McKnight \n| first1 = Tom L \n| last2 = Hess \n| first2 = Darrel \n| year = 2000 \n| chapter = Climate Zones and Types \n| title = Physical Geography: A Landscape Appreciation \n| pages = [https://archive.org/details/physicalgeographmckn/page/205 205&ndash;8] \n| location = Upper Saddle River, NJ \n| publisher = Prentice Hall \n| isbn = 978-0-13-020263-5 \n| url = https://archive.org/details/physicalgeographmckn/page/205 \n}}</ref>\n\nWhen tropical rain forest climates are more dominated by the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] (ITCZ) than the trade winds (and with no or rare cyclones), so usually located near the equator, they are also called equatorial climates. Otherwise, when they are more dominated by the trade winds than the ITCZ, they are called tropical trade-wind climates. In pure equatorial climates, the atmospheric pressure is low, almost constant so the (horizontal) pressure gradient is low. Consequently the winds are rare and usually weak (except sea and land breezes in coastal areas) while in tropical trade-wind climates, often located at higher latitudes than the equatorial climates, wind is almost permanent which incidentally explains why rainforest formations are impoverished compared to those of equatorial climates due to their necessary resistance to strong winds accompanying tropical disturbances.<ref>Climatologie Pierre Estienne Alain Godard, pages 309 and 316</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Rainbow Jungle.jpg|thumb|upright=2.25|right|Upland rain forest in Borneo. Sabah, Malaysia]] A tropical rain forest climate is usually found at [[latitude]]s within 15 degrees North and South of the [[equator]], which are dominated by the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] (ITCZ). The climate is most commonly found in [[South America]], [[Central Africa]], [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Oceania]]. These rain forests are uniformly and monotonously wet throughout the year. Locations in [[Oceania]], areas along the  coast of [[South America|South]] and [[Central America]], from [[Ecuador]] to [[Belize]], parts of [[Central Africa]], and much of [[Indonesia]] have this type of climate.\n\n==Notable cities with tropical rain forest climates==\n<div float=\"left\">\n{{col-begin|width=70%}}\n{{col-1-of-2}}\n'''Africa'''\n* [[Moroni, Comoros|Moroni]], Comoros\n* [[Kisumu]], [[Kenya]]\n* [[Harper, Liberia|Harper]], [[Liberia]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Antalaha]], [[Madagascar]]\n* [[Manakara]], Madagascar\n* [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n\n'''Americas'''\n* [[Punta Gorda, Belize|Punta Gorda]], [[Belize]]\n* [[Lim\u00f3n]], [[Costa Rica]]\n* [[Hig\u00fcey (city)|Hig\u00fcey]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n* [[Puerto Barrios]], [[Guatemala]]\n* [[La Ceiba]], [[Honduras]]\n* [[Port Antonio]], [[Jamaica]]\n* [[Bluefields]], [[Nicaragua]]\n* [[Changuinola]], [[Panama]]\n* [[Bel\u00e9m]], [[Brazil]] ''(equatorial climate)''\n* [[Maca\u00e9]], Brazil\n* [[Salvador, Bahia|Sa