 Lectures on Chinese Poetry |volume=Volume 2 |editor-first=Grace S. |editor-last=Fong |location=Montreal |publisher=Center for East Asian Research, McGill University |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book  |title=[[Zizhi Tongjian]] |year=1084 |volume=vols. [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377195|195]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377199|199]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377200|200]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377201|201]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377202|202]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377203|203]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377204|204]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377205|205]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377206|206]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377207|207]], [[:zh:s:\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377208|208]] |language=Chinese |ref={{harvid|Zizhi Tongjian|1084}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last = Barrett |first = Timothy Hugh |title = The Woman Who Discovered Printing |year=2008 |publisher = [[Yale University Press]] |ISBN = 978-0-300-12728-7 }}\n* {{cite book |title = Daughter of Heaven \u2013 The True Story of the Only Woman to become Emperor of China |last= Cawthorne |first=Nigel |year = 2007 |publisher = One World Publications |location = Oxford, England |ISBN = 978-1-85168-530-1 |ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Jonathan Clements |first=Jonathan |last=Clements |title=Wu: The Chinese Empress Who Schemed, Seduced and Murdered Her Way to Become a Living God |location=Stroud |publisher= Sutton |year= 2007 |ISBN=9780750939614|ref = harv}}\u2014offers a critical appraisal of many primary sources and includes an appendix comparing fictional accounts.\n* {{cite book |last=Guisso |first=Richard W.L. |title=Wu Tse-t'ien and the Politics of Legitimation in T'ang China |location=Bellingham |publisher=Western Washington |year=1978 |url=https://cedar.wwu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?filename=0&article=1028&context=easpress&type=additional |ref = harv}}\u2014a scholarly biography\n* {{cite book |last=Rothschild |first=N. Harry |title=Wu Zhao: China's Only Woman Emperor |publisher=Pearson Education |year=2008 |ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |title = Empress Wu Zetian in Fiction and in History: Female Defiance in Confucian China |first=Dora |last=Shu-fang Dien |publisher=Nova Publishing |year=2003 |ref = harv}}\u2014explores the life of Empress Wu Zetian and the ways women found to participate in public life, despite the societal constraints of dynastic China.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Empress Wu Ze Tian}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[Zhou dynasty (690\u2013705)|Zhou dynasty]]||624|16 December|705}}\n{{S-reg}}\n{{S-new|reason=[[Zhou dynasty (690\u2013705)|Zhou Dynasty proclaimed]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of rulers of China#Tang dynasty|Empress regnant of the Zhou Dynasty]]|years=16 October 690 \u2013 22 February 705}}\n{{S-non|reason=[[Zhou dynasty (690\u2013705)|Tang Dynasty restored]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Emperor Ruizong of Tang|Li D\u00e0n, Emperor Ruizong]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Emperor of China|Empress regnant of China]]|years=16 October 690 \u2013 22 February 705}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Emperor Zhongzong of Tang|Li Xian, Emperor Zhongzong]]}}\n{{s-roy|cn}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Empress Wang (Gaozong)|Empress Wang]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Chinese consorts|Empress consort of the Tang dynasty]]|years=2 December 655 \u2013 27 December 683}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Empress Wei (Tang dynasty)|Empress Wei]]}}\n{{s-hon}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n{{s-vac|last=[[Emperor Gaozu of Tang|Li Yuan, Emperor Gaozu]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Taishang Huang|Retired Empress regnant of China]]|years=22 February 705 \u2013 16 December 705}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Emperor Ruizong of Tang|Li D\u00e0n, Emperor Ruizong]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Tang emperors}}\n{{Tang Dynasty Buddhists}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wu, Zetian}}\n[[Category:624 births]]\n[[Category:705 deaths]]\n[[Category:7th-century Chinese monarchs]]\n[[Category:7th-century Chinese poets]]\n[[Category:7th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:7th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:8th-century Chinese monarchs]]\n[[Category:8th-century Chinese poets]]\n[[Category:8th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:8th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese emperors]]\n[[Category:Chinese women poets]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty imperial consorts]]\n[[Category:Empresses regnant]]\n[[Category:Filicides]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty empresses dowager]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty empresses]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty poets]]\n[[Category:Women leaders of China]]\n[[Category:Wu Zetian| ]]\n[[Category:Tang Taizong]]\n[[Category:Usurpers]]\n[[Category:8th-century Chinese women]]\n[[Category:8th-century Chinese people]]\n[[Category:Chinese Buddhist monarchs]]\n[[Category:Buddhism and women]]\n[[Category:Chinese concubines]]\n", "name_user": "109.125.147.197", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wu_Zetian"}
{"title_page": "Three Dollar Bill, Y'all", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Three Dollar Bill, Y'all\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[Limp Bizkit]]\n| cover      = Limp Bizkit Three Dollar Bill Y'All.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 1, 1997\n| recorded   = May 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Indigo Ranch Studio, [[Malibu, California]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Nu metal]]<ref name=Erlewine />\n*[[rap metal]]<ref name=MSG />\n}}\n| length     = 61:26\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]]\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Ross Robinson]]\n* Limp Bizkit\n}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Significant Other (album)|Significant Other]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\n | single1date = August 26, 1997\n | single2     = Nobody Loves Me\n | single2date = October 29, 1997\n | single3     = Sour\n | single3date = March 17, 1998\n | single4     = [[Faith (Limp Bizkit song)|Faith]]\n | single4date = October 31, 1998\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all''''' (stylized as '''''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$''''') is the debut [[studio album]] by American [[rap rock]] band [[Limp Bizkit]], released on July 1, 1997 by [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]] and [[Interscope Records]]. It established the band's trademark sound with the [[single (music)|singles]] \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\", which was influenced by [[hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], and \"[[Faith (Limp Bizkit song)|Faith]]\", a cover of the song of the same name by [[George Michael]]. Limp Bizkit's rearrangement of the song incorporated heavier guitar playing by [[Wes Borland]] and [[turntablism|scratching]] by [[DJ Lethal]].\n\n''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$'' was produced by [[Ross Robinson]], who was introduced to the band through [[Korn]] bassist [[Reginald Arvizu]], who persuaded Robinson to listen to Limp Bizkit's [[demo (music)|demo]]. Robinson was impressed by the band's motivation and sound, and agreed to work with them. The album showcased an intentionally abrasive, angry sound which the band felt would attract a fanbase.\n\n==Production==\n[[Wes Borland]] left Limp Bizkit preceding a successful performance opening for Korn at the Dragonfly in Hollywood due to a disagreement with Fred Durst, Limp Bizkit signed with [[Mojo Records|Mojo]], a subsidiary of [[MCA Records]]. While heading to California to record their first album, the band wrecked their van, leading Durst to rehire Borland.<ref name=Devenish36/> After a dispute with Mojo, Limp Bizkit signed with [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]], a subsidiary of [[Interscope Records]].<ref name=Devenish36/>\n\n[[Reginald Arvizu]] of the band [[Korn]] persuaded [[Ross Robinson]] to listen to the band's demo, which consisted of the songs \"Pollution\", \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\" and \"Stuck\". Robinson finally listened to the tape after it was praised by Robinson's girlfriend. Robinson was impressed by the band's motivation and sound, and produced their debut, which was recorded at Indigo Ranch.<ref name=Devenish36/> During the recording sessions, the band recorded an early version of their song \"I'm Broke\", but it was decided that the song didn't fit on this album. It was subsequently reworked and recorded for their followup, ''[[Significant Other (album)|Significant Other]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |page=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/89 89] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/89 }}</ref>\n\nContinuing the band's policy of using names that would repulse potential listeners, the band named the album by using part of the phrase \"queer as a three dollar bill\" and adding the word \"Y'all\" for Florida flavor, naming the album ''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$''.<ref name=Devenish36>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/36 36\u201349] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/36 }}</ref>\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n{{Listen\n|filename=Counterfeit.ogg\n|title=\"Counterfeit\"\n|description=\"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\", which appears on ''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$', is noted for its \"kinetic, frenzied energy\" and a mix of music styles.\n|filename2=Nobody Loves Me.ogg\n|title2=\"Nobody Loves Me\"\n|description2=This breakdown from the song \"Nobody Loves Me\" was inspired by the  band [[Tool (band)|Tool]]. Limp Bizkit vocalist Fred Durst imitates the singing style of [[Maynard James Keenan]] in this sample.}}\n\nThe band was inspired to write \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\" after local bands began to copy their style. According to Borland, \"They saw this little thing we built [...] and they were like, 'Oh, let's get baggy pants and dress like kind of [[hip hop|hip-hoppy]] and, you know, play [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[rapping|rap]].' [...] five or six bands just popped up out of nowhere that became these, you know, groups that were trying to sound like us. It was ridiculous. That's where the song 'Counterfeit' came from.\"<ref name=Devenish36/>\n\n[[Fred Durst]]'s problems with his girlfriend inspired him to write the song \"Sour\".<ref name=Devenish36/> The mood and tone set by Robinson in the studio allowed the band to improvise; a recording of the band improvising appeared as the last track on the album, \"Everything\".<ref name=Devenish36/> The recording of the album also allowed the band to showcase the addition of [[DJ Lethal]], and experimental guitar playing by Borland, who played without a [[guitar pick]], performing with right hand fingers.\nOn the song \"Stuck\", Borland used a sustain pedal in the first bar, and muted riffs in the second bar.<ref name=HurwitzRiley/> Borland's playing on this album features octave shapes, and choppy, eighth-note rhythms, sometimes accompanied by muting his strings with his left hand, creating a percussive sound.<ref name=HurwitzRiley>{{cite book |last1=Hurwitz |first1=Tobias |authorlink1= |last2=Riley |first2=Glenn |title=7-String Guitar |date=June 1, 2002 |publisher=Alfred Music Publishing |isbn=0-7390-2807-3 |pages=30\u20132 |chapter=Rhythm guitar riffs in the style of Wes Borland }}</ref> Borland also made use of unevenly accented syncopated sixteenth notes and hypnotic, droning [[Lick (music)|licks]] to create a disorienting effect.<ref name=HurwitzRiley/>\n\nDespite the success of live performances of the band's cover of [[George Michael]]'s song \"[[Faith (George Michael song)|Faith]]\", Robinson was opposed to recording the cover, and tried to persuade the band not to play it on the album. However, the final recording, which incorporated heavier guitar playing and drumming, as well as DJ scratching, impressed Robinson.<ref name=Devenish36/> Robinson also bonded with Borland, who Robinson perceived as not taking the band seriously.<ref name=Devenish36/> The [[alternative metal]] band [[Tool (band)|Tool]] provided a strong influence in shaping the album's sound, particularly in the song \"Nobody Loves Me\", which contains a breakdown in which Durst copied the singing of [[Maynard James Keenan]] and the intro which has elements of ''[[Undertow (Tool album)|Undertow]]'' hidden track \"Disgustipated\".<ref name=Devenish36/>\n\nThe completed album featured an abrasive, angry sound which Borland later stated was part of Limp Bizkit's plan to get noticed. \"The best way to get our message across is through shock value. That's what grabs people [...] getting people to react by showing something negative, hoping something positive will come out of it. Trying to stay in reality.\"<ref name=Devenish36/> This sound has been described as [[nu metal]]<ref name=Erlewine>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r278011/review |title=''Three Dollar Bill Y'All'' - Limp Bizkit |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> and [[rapcore]].<ref name=MSG>{{cite book |last1=Apter |first1=Jeff |title=Never Enough: The Story of The Cure |year=2009 |publisher=Music Sales Group |isbn=0-85712-024-7 |page=468 |chapter= }}</ref>\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all'' was released by Interscope Records on July 1, 1997, only a month after it had been recorded. Some sites list the album's release date as being June 24, 1997 rather than July 1, 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001NY9YJA/ref=dm_ws_sp_ps_dp |title=Three Dollar Bill, Y'all $ by Limp Bizkit on Amazon Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\nAfter the album's release, Limp Bizkit opened for [[Faith No More]] on the American leg of their ''[[Album of the Year (Faith No More album)|Album of the Year]]'' tour,<ref name=\"faithnomorebook\">{{cite web|author=Jay Gabler |url=https://www.thecurrent.org/feature/2019/01/15/faith-no-more-small-victories |title=Rock and Roll Book Club: 'Small Victories' tells the story of Faith No More |publisher=The Current |date= |accessdate=2019-06-25}}</ref> which was the group's final tour before their break up the following year. Despite citing Faith No More as one of their biggest influences, guitarist Wes Borland has spoken of how touring with them in 1997 was a negative experience for the band.<ref>Borland, Wes. 2017. ''Talk Toomey'' Podcast</ref> At one show opening for Faith No More, Fred Durst referred to the audience as \"faggots\" when they started booing Limp Bizkit. Following this show, Durst apologized to Faith No More's keyboardist [[Roddy Bottum]], who unbeknownst to him had come out as [[homosexual|gay]] in the early 90s.<ref name=\"faithnomorebook\"/> Earlier in 1997, before the album's release, Limp Bizkit had performed with Korn and [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]], two other artists they have cited as influences. <!-- Sourced via Devenish book -->\n\nIn 1998, controversy erupted when it was revealed Interscope paid $5,000 to guarantee that a Portland radio station play the song \"Counterfeit\" fifty times, preceded and concluded with an announcement that the air time was paid for by Interscope.<ref name=Devenish51>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/51 51\u201378] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/51 }}</ref><ref name=MTVJuly1998>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431305/limp-bizkit-pays-counterfeit-play.jhtml |title=Limp Bizkit Pays For 'Counterfeit' Play |author= |date=July 1, 1998 |work= |publisher=[[MTV News]] |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> The paid air time was criticized by the media, who saw it as \"[[payola]]\".<ref name=Devenish51/><ref name=MTVJuly1998/> The band's manager Jeff Kwatinetz later termed the plan as a \"brilliant marketing move\".<ref name=Devenish51/> Durst stated, \"It worked, but it's not that cool of a thing.\"<ref name=Devenish51/> Despite criticism, the paid air time did not increase sales, which stood at only 170,000 in early 1998.  Much of the album's resulting sales instead came from consistent touring by the band.<ref name=Devenish51/>\n\nDurst directed a music video for the band's single \"Faith\" in promotion for its appearance in the film ''[[Very Bad Things]]'', but was unsatisfied with it, and directed a second video which paid tribute to tourmates like [[Primus (band)|Primus]], [[Deftones]] and [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], who appeared in the video.<ref name=Devenish51/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=Erlewine/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Martin C. Strong]]''\n| rev2Score = 7/10<ref name=\"Strong\">{{cite book |last1=Strong |first1=Martin Charles  |title=The Essential Rock Discography |edition=8th |year=2006 |publisher=Open City Books |isbn=1-84195-860-3 |page=638 |chapter=Limp Bizkit }}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Robert Christgau]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating-Christgau|dud}}<ref name=Christgau/>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=RollingStoneAlbumGuide>{{cite book |title=The new Rolling Stone album guide |last= |first= |editor1-first=Nathan |editor1-last=Brackett |editor2-first=Christian |editor2-last=Hoard |publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2004 |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/n500 487] |chapter=Limp Bizkit |url=https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac|url-access=registration |quote=rolling stone limp bizkit album guide. }}</ref>\n}}\n''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$'' received mostly positive reviews from critics. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[Allmusic]] praised the album, writing \"They might not have many original ideas [...] but they do the sound well. They have a powerful rhythm section and memorable hooks, most of which make up for the uneven songwriting.\"<ref name=Erlewine/> In ''The Essential Rock Discography'', Martin Charles Strong gave the album a 7 out of 10 rating.<ref name=\"Strong\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album a negative review.<ref name=Christgau>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Limp+Bizkit |title=Review of ''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$'' |author=Christgau, Robert |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> Borland stated in an interview that George Michael, the writer of the song \"Faith\", hated Limp Bizkit's cover and \"hates us for doing it\".<ref name=Devenish51/> Through extensive touring and the band's later breakthrough into the mainstream, the album went [[RIAA certification|double platinum]] in 2001.<ref name=Erlewine/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsort.info/music/8fb98h.htm |title=Album artist 279 - Limp Bizkit |publisher=Tsort.info |date= |accessdate=2012-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = \n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = \n| total_length    = 60:01/61:26\n| all_lyrics      = [[Fred Durst]] except \"Faith\" by [[George Michael]]\n| all_music       = [[Limp Bizkit]] except \"Faith\" by Michael\n| title1          = Intro\n| length1         = 0:48\n| title2          = Pollution\n| length2         = 3:52\n| title3          = [[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\n| length3         = 5:08\n| title4          = Stuck\n| length4         = 5:21\n| title5          = Nobody Loves Me\n| length5         = 4:33\n| title6          = Sour\n| length6         = 3:33\n| title7          = Stalemate\n| length7         = 6:13\n| title8          = Clunk\n| length8         = 4:03\n| title9          = [[Faith (Limp Bizkit song)|Faith]]\n| note9           = contains a hidden track titled \"Stereotype Me\" starting at 2:27\n| length9         = 3:52\n| title10         = Stink Finger\n| length10        = 3:03\n| title11         = Indigo Flow\n| length11        = 2:23\n| title12         = Leech <!-- That's what it says on the back of the album. Do not change to \"Leech\". -->\n| note12 = demo version\n| length12        = 2:11\n| title13         = Everything\n| length13        = 16:26\n\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Limp Bizkit===\n* [[Sam Rivers (bassist)|Sam Rivers]] - [[Bass guitar|bass]], [[backing vocals]]\n* [[DJ Lethal]] - [[Phonograph|turntables]], [[Sampling (music)|samples]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[programming (music)|programming]], [[Sound collage|sound development]]\n* [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]] - [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n* [[Fred Durst]] - [[Singing|lead vocals]], art direction, cover art\n* [[Wes Borland]] - [[guitar]]s, [[backing vocals]]\n\n===Production===\n* [[Ross Robinson]] - Producer\n* Richard Kaplan - Engineer\n* [[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] - Mixing\n* [[Steve Sisco]] - Mixing\n* [[Howie Weinberg]] - Mastering\n* [[Tom Simpson]] - [[Digital media|Media]]\n* [[Jordan Schur]] - Executive Producer, A&R\n* Tom Whalley - A&R direction\n* Jill Rose - A&R Coordination\n* [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]] (Flip) - Layout\n* [[Scott Borland]] - Keyboard on tracks 1,2, and 6\n\n==Charts==\n'''Albums''' - Billboard (United States)/RPM (Canada)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:550px;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Year\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Chart\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Position\n|-  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"\n||1998\n||Heatseekers\n||1\n|-  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"\n||1998\n||The Billboard 200\n||22\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|1999\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Canadian Albums Chart\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|29<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7442&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|title=Top Albums/CDs - Volume 68, No. 24, April 05 1999 |magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=2010-10-09 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n'''Singles''' - Billboard (United States)/RPM (Canada)\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:550px;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Year\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Single\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Chart\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Position\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|1998\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|\"Faith\"\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Alternative 30\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|30<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7005&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|title=Rock/Alternative - Volume 68, No. 12, December 14, 1998|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=2010-10-28 }}</ref>\n|-  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"\n||1999\n||\"Faith\"\n||Mainstream Rock Tracks\n||33\n|-  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"\n||1999\n||\"Faith\"\n||Modern Rock Tracks\n||28\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Limp Bizkit}}\n\n[[Category:1997 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ross Robinson]]\n[[Category:Flip Records (1994) albums]]\n[[Category:Limp Bizkit albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Three Dollar Bill, Y'all\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[Limp Bizkit]]\n| cover      = Limp Bizkit Three Dollar Bill Y'All.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 1, 1997\n| recorded   = May 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Indigo Ranch Studio, [[Malibu, California]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Nu metal]]<ref name=Erlewine />\n*[[rap metal]]<ref name=MSG />\n}}\n| length     = 61:26\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]]\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Ross Robinson]]\n* Limp Bizkit\n}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Significant Other (album)|Significant Other]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\n | single1date = August 26, 1997\n | single2     = Nobody Loves Me\n | single2date = October 29, 1997\n | single3     = Sour\n | single3date = March 17, 1998\n | single4     = [[Faith (Limp Bizkit song)|Faith]]\n | single4date = October 31, 1998\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all''''' (stylized as '''''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$''''') is the debut [[studio album]] by American [[rap rock]] band [[Limp Bizkit]], released on July 1, 1997 by [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]] and [[Interscope Records]]. It established the band's trademark sound with the [[single (music)|singles]] \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\", which was influenced by [[hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], and \"[[Faith (Limp Bizkit song)|Faith]]\", a cover of the song of the same name by [[George Michael]]. Limp Bizkit's rearrangement of the song incorporated heavier guitar playing by [[Wes Borland]] and [[turntablism|scratching]] by [[DJ Lethal]].\n\n''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$'' was produced by [[Ross Robinson]], who was introduced to the band through [[Korn]] bassist [[Reginald Arvizu]], who persuaded Robinson to listen to Limp Bizkit's [[demo (music)|demo]]. Robinson was impressed by the band's motivation and sound, and agreed to work with them. The album showcased an intentionally abrasive, angry sound which the band felt would attract a fanbase.\n\n==Production==\n[[Wes Borland]] left Limp Bizkit preceding a successful performance opening for Korn at the Dragonfly in Hollywood due to a disagreement with Fred Durst, Limp Bizkit signed with [[Mojo Records|Mojo]], a subsidiary of [[MCA Records]]. While heading to California to record their first album, the band wrecked their van, leading Durst to rehire Borland.<ref name=Devenish36/> After a dispute with Mojo, Limp Bizkit signed with [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]], a subsidiary of [[Interscope Records]].<ref name=Devenish36/>\n\n[[Reginald Arvizu]] of the band [[Korn]] persuaded [[Ross Robinson]] to listen to the band's demo, which consisted of the songs \"Pollution\", \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\" and \"Stuck\". Robinson finally listened to the tape after it was praised by Robinson's girlfriend. Robinson was impressed by the band's motivation and sound, and produced their debut, which was recorded at Indigo Ranch.<ref name=Devenish36/> During the recording sessions, the band recorded an early version of their song \"I'm Broke\", but it was decided that the song didn't fit on this album. It was subsequently reworked and recorded for their followup, ''[[Significant Other (album)|Significant Other]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |page=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/89 89] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/89 }}</ref>\n\nContinuing the band's policy of using names that would repulse potential listeners, the band named the album by using part of the phrase \"queer as a three dollar bill\" and adding the word \"Y'all\" for Florida flavor, naming the album ''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$''.<ref name=Devenish36>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/36 36\u201349] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/36 }}</ref>\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n{{Listen\n|filename=Counterfeit.ogg\n|title=\"Counterfeit\"\n|description=\"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\", which appears on ''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$', is noted for its \"kinetic, frenzied energy\" and a mix of music styles.\n|filename2=Nobody Loves Me.ogg\n|title2=\"Nobody Loves Me\"\n|description2=This breakdown from the song \"Nobody Loves Me\" was inspired by the  band [[Tool (band)|Tool]]. Limp Bizkit vocalist Fred Durst imitates the singing style of [[Maynard James Keenan]] in this sample.}}\n\nThe band was inspired to write \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\" after local bands began to copy their style. According to Borland, \"They saw this little thing we built [...] and they were like, 'Oh, let's get baggy pants and dress like kind of [[hip hop|hip-hoppy]] and, you know, play [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[rapping|rap]].' [...] five or six bands just popped up out of nowhere that became these, you know, groups that were trying to sound like us. It was ridiculous. That's where the song 'Counterfeit' came from.\"<ref name=Devenish36/>\n\n[[Fred Durst]]'s problems with his girlfriend inspired him to write the song \"Sour\".<ref name=Devenish36/> The mood and tone set by Robinson in the studio allowed the band to improvise; a recording of the band improvising appeared as the last track on the album, \"Everything\".<ref name=Devenish36/> The recording of the album also allowed the band to showcase the addition of [[DJ Lethal]], and experimental guitar playing by Borland, who played without a [[guitar pick]], performing with right hand fingers.\nOn the song \"Stuck\", Borland used a sustain pedal in the first bar, and muted riffs in the second bar.<ref name=HurwitzRiley/> Borland's playing on this album features octave shapes, and choppy, eighth-note rhythms, sometimes accompanied by muting his strings with his left hand, creating a percussive sound.<ref name=HurwitzRiley>{{cite book |last1=Hurwitz |first1=Tobias |authorlink1= |last2=Riley |first2=Glenn |title=7-String Guitar |date=June 1, 2002 |publisher=Alfred Music Publishing |isbn=0-7390-2807-3 |pages=30\u20132 |chapter=Rhythm guitar riffs in the style of Wes Borland }}</ref> Borland also made use of unevenly accented syncopated sixteenth notes and hypnotic, droning [[Lick (music)|licks]] to create a disorienting effect.<ref name=HurwitzRiley/> \n\nDespite the success of live performances of the band's cover of [[George Michael]]'s song \"[[Faith (George Michael song)|Faith]]\", Robinson was opposed to recording the cover, and tried to persuade the band not to play it on the album. However, the final recording, which incorporated heavier guitar playing and drumming, as well as DJ scratching, impressed Robinson.<ref name=Devenish36/> Robinson also bonded with Borland, who Robinson perceived as not taking the band seriously.<ref name=Devenish36/> The [[alternative metal]] band [[Tool (band)|Tool]] provided a strong influence in shaping the album's sound, particularly in the song \"Nobody Loves Me\", which contains a breakdown in which Durst copied the singing of [[Maynard James Keenan]] and the intro which has elements of ''[[Undertow (Tool album)|Undertow]]'' hidden track \"Disgustipated\".<ref name=Devenish36/>\n\nThe completed album featured an abrasive, angry sound which Borland later stated was part of Limp Bizkit's plan to get noticed. \"The best way to get our message across is through shock value. That's what grabs people [...] getting people to react by showing something negative, hoping something positive will come out of it. Trying to stay in reality.\"<ref name=Devenish36/> This sound has been described as [[nu metal]]<ref name=Erlewine>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r278011/review |title=''Three Dollar Bill Y'All'' - Limp Bizkit |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> and [[rapcore]].<ref name=MSG>{{cite book |last1=Apter |first1=Jeff |title=Never Enough: The Story of The Cure |year=2009 |publisher=Music Sales Group |isbn=0-85712-024-7 |page=468 |chapter= }}</ref>\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all'' was released by Interscope Records on July 1, 1997, only a month after it had been recorded. Some sites list the album's release date as being June 24, 1997 rather than July 1, 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001NY9YJA/ref=dm_ws_sp_ps_dp |title=Three Dollar Bill, Y'all $ by Limp Bizkit on Amazon Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\nAfter the album's release, Limp Bizkit opened for [[Faith No More]] on the American leg of their ''[[Album of the Year (Faith No More album)|Album of the Year]]'' tour,<ref name=\"faithnomorebook\">{{cite web|author=Jay Gabler |url=https://www.thecurrent.org/feature/2019/01/15/faith-no-more-small-victories |title=Rock and Roll Book Club: 'Small Victories' tells the story of Faith No More |publisher=The Current |date= |accessdate=2019-06-25}}</ref> which was the group's final tour before their break up the following year. Despite citing Faith No More as one of their biggest influences, guitarist Wes Borland has spoken of how touring with them in 1997 was a negative experience for the band.<ref>Borland, Wes. 2017. ''Talk Toomey'' Podcast</ref> At one show opening for Faith No More, Fred Durst referred to the audience as \"faggots\" when they started booing Limp Bizkit. Following this show, Durst apologized to Faith No More's keyboardist [[Roddy Bottum]], who unbeknownst to him had come out as [[homosexual|gay]] in the early 90s.<ref name=\"faithnomorebook\"/> Earlier in 1997, before the album's release, Limp Bizkit had performed with Korn and [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]], two other artists they have cited as influences. <!-- Sourced via Devenish book -->\n\nIn 1998, controversy erupted when it was revealed Interscope payed $5,000 to guarantee that a Portland radio station play the song \"Counterfeit\" fifty times, preceded and concluded with an announcement that the air time was paid for by Interscope.<ref name=Devenish51>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/51 51\u201378] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/51 }}</ref><ref name=MTVJuly1998>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431305/limp-bizkit-pays-counterfeit-play.jhtml |title=Limp Bizkit Pays For 'Counterfeit' Play |author= |date=July 1, 1998 |work= |publisher=[[MTV News]] |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> The paid air time was criticized by the media, who saw it as \"[[payola]]\".<ref name=Devenish51/><ref name=MTVJuly1998/> The band's manager Jeff Kwatinetz later termed the plan as a \"brilliant marketing move\".<ref name=Devenish51/> Durst stated, \"It worked, but it's not that cool of a thing.\"<ref name=Devenish51/> Despite criticism, the paid air time did not increase sales, which stood at only 170,000 in early 1998.  Much of the album's resulting sales instead came from consistent touring by the band.<ref name=Devenish51/> \n\nDurst directed a music video for the band's single \"Faith\" in promotion for its appearance in the film ''[[Very Bad Things]]'', but was unsatisfied with it, and directed a second video which paid tribute to tourmates like [[Primus (band)|Primus]], [[Deftones]] and [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], who appeared in the video.<ref name=Devenish51/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=Erlewine/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Martin C. Strong]]''\n| rev2Score = 7/10<ref name=\"Strong\">{{cite book |last1=Strong |first1=Martin Charles  |title=The Essential Rock Discography |edition=8th |year=2006 |publisher=Open City Books |isbn=1-84195-860-3 |page=638 |chapter=Limp Bizkit }}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Robert Christgau]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating-Christgau|dud}}<ref name=Christgau/>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=RollingStoneAlbumGuide>{{cite book |title=The new Rolling Stone album guide |last= |first= |editor1-first=Nathan |editor1-last=Brackett |editor2-first=Christian |editor2-last=Hoard |publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2004 |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/n500 487] |chapter=Limp Bizkit |url=https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac|url-access=registration |quote=rolling stone limp bizkit album guide. }}</ref>\n}}\n''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$'' received mostly positive reviews from critics. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[Allmusic]] praised the album, writing \"They might not have many original ideas [...] but they do the sound well. They have a powerful rhythm section and memorable hooks, most of which make up for the uneven songwriting.\"<ref name=Erlewine/> In ''The Essential Rock Discography'', Martin Charles Strong gave the album a 7 out of 10 rating.<ref name=\"Strong\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album a negative review.<ref name=Christgau>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Limp+Bizkit |title=Review of ''Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$'' |author=Christgau, Robert |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> Borland stated in an interview that George Michael, the writer of the song \"Faith\", hated Limp Bizkit's cover and \"hates us for doing it\".<ref name=Devenish51/> Through extensive touring and the band's later breakthrough into the mainstream, the album went [[RIAA certification|double platinum]] in 2001.<ref name=Erlewine/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsort.info/music/8fb98h.htm |title=Album artist 279 - Limp Bizkit |publisher=Tsort.info |date= |accessdate=2012-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = \n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = \n| total_length    = 60:01/61:26\n| all_lyrics      = [[Fred Durst]] except \"Faith\" by [[George Michael]]\n| all_music       = [[Limp Bizkit]] except \"Faith\" by Michael\n| title1          = Intro\n| length1         = 0:48\n| title2          = Pollution\n| length2         = 3:52\n| title3          = [[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\n| length3         = 5:08\n| title4          = Stuck\n| length4         = 5:21\n| title5          = Nobody Loves Me\n| length5         = 4:33\n| title6          = Sour\n| length6         = 3:33\n| title7          = Stalemate\n| length7         = 6:13\n| title8          = Clunk\n| length8         = 4:03\n| title9          = [[Faith (Limp Bizkit song)|Faith]]\n| note9           = contains a hidden track titled \"Stereotype Me\" starting at 2:27\n| length9         = 3:52\n| title10         = Stink Finger\n| length10        = 3:03\n| title11         = Indigo Flow\n| length11        = 2:23\n| title12         = Leech <!-- That's what it says on the back of the album. Do not change to \"Leech\". -->\n| note12 = demo version\n| length12        = 2:11\n| title13         = Everything\n| length13        = 16:26\n\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Limp Bizkit===\n* [[Sam Rivers (bassist)|Sam Rivers]] - [[Bass guitar|bass]], [[backing vocals]]\n* [[DJ Lethal]] - [[Phonograph|turntables]], [[Sampling (music)|samples]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[programming (music)|programming]], [[Sound collage|sound development]]\n* [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]] - [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n* [[Fred Durst]] - [[Singing|lead vocals]], art direction, cover art\n* [[Wes Borland]] - [[guitar]]s, [[backing vocals]]\n\n===Production===\n* [[Ross Robinson]] - Producer\n* Richard Kaplan - Engineer\n* [[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] - Mixing\n* [[Steve Sisco]] - Mixing\n* [[Howie Weinberg]] - Mastering\n* [[Tom Simpson]] - [[Digital media|Media]]\n* [[Jordan Schur]] - Executive Producer, A&R\n* Tom Whalley - A&R direction\n* Jill Rose - A&R Coordination\n* [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]] (Flip) - Layout\n* [[Scott Borland]] - Keyboard on tracks 1,2, and 6\n\n==Charts==\n'''Albums''' - Billboard (United States)/RPM (Canada)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:550px;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Year\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Chart\n!  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Position\n|-  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"\n||1998\n||Heatseekers\n||1\n|-  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"\n||1998\n||The Billboard 200\n||22\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|1999\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|Canadian Albums Chart\n|  style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"|29<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7442&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|title=Top Albums/CDs - Volume 68, No. 24, April 05 1999 |magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=2010-10-09 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n'''Singles''' - Billboard (United States)/RPM (Canada)\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:550px;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:left