tps://news.softpedia.com/news/Deciphering-the-Language-of-the-Brain-Brought-Closer-192893.shtml|title=Deciphering the Language of the Brain Brought Closer|last=Vieru|first=Tudor|website=softpedia|language=english|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nAccording to an interview, Sharpee grew up with a grandfather for a scientist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fairhalllab.com/careers/how-does-she-do-it/|title=How does she do it?|date=2013-06-18|website=Fairhall lab|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> and always aspired for the same. She obtained her [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] from [[Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv]] in [[Ukraine]], and moved on to [[Michigan State University]] for her [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[theoretical physics]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.emedevents.com/speaker-profile/tatyana-sharpee|title=Tatyana Sharpee - Assistant Professor of Neuroscience in La Jolla, California, United States of America {{!}} eMedEvents|website=www.emedevents.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> In 2015, she received a [[National Science Foundation]] grant to study feature selectivity and invariance in deep neural architectures. Her work has been focused on probing how our brains represent complex transformations of the same object to recognize it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salk.edu/news-release/salk-computational-neurobiologist-receives-nsf-grant-study-brain-processes-sound/|title=Salk computational neurobiologist receives NSF grant to study how brain processes sound|website=Salk Institute for Biological Studies|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Sharpee  uses state-of-the-art deep learning algorithms to understand where the algorithms are failing at complex object transformations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://physics.ucsd.edu/News/Story/250|title=UC San Diego {{!}} Salk Scientist Tatyana Sharpee receives CAREER award from NSF|website=physics.ucsd.edu|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>.  The NSF grant also enabled her lab to study how the auditory system of the brain works based on large scale simulations of neural networks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salk.edu/news-release/salk-computational-neurobiologist-receives-nsf-grant-study-brain-processes-sound/|title=Salk computational neurobiologist receives NSF grant to study how brain processes sound|website=Salk Institute for Biological Studies|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>. This latter work not only has potential to improve the current hearing aid technology, but also could reveal therapeutic paths to treat a number of attention deficit and psychiatric disorders which depend on the corresponding system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salk.edu/news-release/salk-computational-neurobiologist-receives-nsf-grant-study-brain-processes-sound/|title=Salk computational neurobiologist receives NSF grant to study how brain processes sound|website=Salk Institute for Biological Studies|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nPost graduate school, Sharpee joined the [[University of California, San Francisco|University of California San Fransisco]] for from 2001-2007 as a Sloan-Swartz fellow,<ref name=\":0\" /> where the bulk of her work revolved around [[computational neuroscience]]. She then joined [[University of California, San Diego|UCSD]] and [[Salk Institute for Biological Studies|the Salk Institute]] as faculty and has been working there since, supervising a number of graduate students in [[physics]], [[neuroscience]] and [[quantitative biology]]. In 2018, Sharpee was elected as a Fellow of the American Physiological Society for her work in Physics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-09/si-sit092518.php|title=Salk Institute's Tatyana Sharpee elected 2018 Fellow of American Physical Society|website=EurekAlert!|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Publications==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salk.edu/scientist/tatyana-sharpee/publications/|title=Publications|website=Salk Institute for Biological Studies|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n* Clifford, C.W.G., Webster, M.A., Stanley, G.B., et al. Visual adaptation: Neural, psychological and computational aspects. ''Vision Research''. 2007; 47(25): 3125-3131, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.visres.2007.08.023\n* Zhou, Y., Smith, B.H., Sharpee, T.O., et al. Hyperbolic geometry of the olfactory space. ''Science Advances.'' 2018; 4(8): eaaq1458, doi: 10.1126/sciadv.aaq1458\n*Sharpee, T.O., Berkowitz, J.A. Linking neural responses to behavior with information-preserving population vectors (2019) ''Current Opinion in Behavioral Sciences.'' 29:37-44. DOI: <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cobeha.2019.03.004</nowiki>\n*Amatya, D.N., Linker, S.B., Mendes, A.P.D., Santos, R., Erikson, G., Shokhirev, M.N., Zhou, Y., Sharpee, T., Gage, F.H., Marchetto, M.C., Kim, Y. Dynamical Electrical Complexity Is Reduced during Neuronal Differentiation in Autism Spectrum Disorder. (2019) ''Stem Cell Reports.'' DOI: 10.1016/j.stemcr.2019.08.001\n*Sharpee, T.O. An argument for hyperbolic geometry in neural circuits. (2019) ''Current Opinion in Neurobiology.'' 58:101-104. DOI: 10.1016/j.conb.2019.07.008\n*Berkowitz, J.A., Sharpee, T.O. Quantifying Information Conveyed by Large Neuronal Populations. (2019) ''Neural Computation.'':1-33 DOI: 10.1162/neco_a_01193\n*Zhou, Y., Smith, B.H., Sharpee, T.O. Hyperbolic geometry of the olfactory space. (2018) ''Science Advances.'' 4(8):eaaq1458. DOI: 10.1126/sciadv.aaq1458\n*Atencio, C.A., Sharpee, T.O. Multidimensional receptive field processing by cat primary auditory cortical neurons. (2017) ''Neuroscience.'' 359:130-141. DOI: 10.1016/j.neuroscience.2017.07.003\n*Sharpee, T.O. On texture, form, and fixational eye movements. (2017) ''Current Opinion in Neurobiology.'' 46:228-233. DOI: 10.1016/j.conb.2017.09.002\n*Kaardal, J.T., Theunissen, F.E., Sharpee, T.O. A Low-Rank Method for Characterizing High-Level Neural Computations. (2017